WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.476 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.476 --> 00:00:02.952 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:02.952 --> 00:00:05.412 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.412 --> 00:00:11.700 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:12.450 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:13.680 align:middle line:90%
Well, we can get started.

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:17.060 align:middle line:84%
So in the first class
we talked about what

00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:19.710 align:middle line:84%
is a projection estimate and
what is projection theory.

00:00:19.710 --> 00:00:22.458 align:middle line:84%
And I tried to give a little
bit of motivation for it.

00:00:22.458 --> 00:00:24.500 align:middle line:84%
And today we'll start
getting our hands on things

00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:27.770 align:middle line:84%
and looking at examples
and proving theorems.

00:00:27.770 --> 00:00:31.520 align:middle line:84%
Now, the cleanest setting
in which to get started

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:33.950 align:middle line:90%
is finite fields.

00:00:33.950 --> 00:00:37.970 align:middle line:84%
And although most of our
class will be working in RN,

00:00:37.970 --> 00:00:40.970 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to start there because
the proofs are very clean

00:00:40.970 --> 00:00:42.390 align:middle line:90%
and the examples are very clean.

00:00:42.390 --> 00:00:46.230 align:middle line:84%
And it is also
interesting in itself.

00:00:46.230 --> 00:00:46.730 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:46.730 --> 00:00:55.690 align:middle line:90%


00:00:55.690 --> 00:00:56.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:56.190 --> 00:00:57.220 align:middle line:90%
So here's our setup.

00:00:57.220 --> 00:01:00.530 align:middle line:90%


00:01:00.530 --> 00:01:05.870 align:middle line:84%
So we'll have Fq, the finite
field with q elements.

00:01:05.870 --> 00:01:12.230 align:middle line:84%
And then theta, so then
I'll have a map pi sub

00:01:12.230 --> 00:01:16.640 align:middle line:90%
theta from Fq squared to Fq.

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:18.410 align:middle line:84%
These are the
different projections

00:01:18.410 --> 00:01:20.070 align:middle line:90%
from Fq squared to Fq.

00:01:20.070 --> 00:01:25.610 align:middle line:84%
And it's defined by
pi theta of X1, X2,

00:01:25.610 --> 00:01:31.960 align:middle line:84%
is X1 times theta or
X1 plus X2 times theta.

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:35.150 align:middle line:90%


00:01:35.150 --> 00:01:37.370 align:middle line:90%
So here theta is also in Fq.

00:01:37.370 --> 00:01:46.760 align:middle line:90%


00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:50.600 align:middle line:84%
So now our setup is that
we'll have a set of points,

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:53.340 align:middle line:90%
X in the plane Fq squared.

00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:55.760 align:middle line:84%
And we'll think about
projecting this set of points

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:57.620 align:middle line:84%
in a bunch of
different directions.

00:01:57.620 --> 00:02:01.610 align:middle line:84%
So then we'll have a set of
directions, which is called D.

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:04.500 align:middle line:90%
So D is a subset of Fq.

00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:06.626 align:middle line:84%
And you think of it as
a set of directions.

00:02:06.626 --> 00:02:11.600 align:middle line:90%


00:02:11.600 --> 00:02:13.312 align:middle line:84%
We're going to imagine
taking this at X

00:02:13.312 --> 00:02:15.770 align:middle line:84%
and projecting it in all of
these different directions that

00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:20.490 align:middle line:84%
are in D. And we'll see how big
the different projections are.

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:23.180 align:middle line:84%
And the thing I'll
measure, I'll call it

00:02:23.180 --> 00:02:26.570 align:middle line:84%
S, which depends on
X And D, is the size

00:02:26.570 --> 00:02:29.300 align:middle line:90%
of the biggest projection.

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:41.780 align:middle line:84%
So it's the maximum theta in D
of the size of pi theta of X.

00:02:41.780 --> 00:02:43.508 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:43.508 --> 00:02:45.590 align:middle line:84%
So one thing we study
in projection theory is

00:02:45.590 --> 00:02:48.380 align:middle line:84%
we'd like to understand for
different sizes of X and D,

00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:59.240 align:middle line:84%
what can we say
about S. So let's

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:01.020 align:middle line:90%
look at a couple of examples.

00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:04.633 align:middle line:84%
And then after that, I'll tell
you some theorems, what we know,

00:03:04.633 --> 00:03:06.050 align:middle line:84%
and some conjecture,
what we think

00:03:06.050 --> 00:03:07.550 align:middle line:84%
might be true based
on the examples.

00:03:07.550 --> 00:03:13.160 align:middle line:90%


00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:20.340 align:middle line:84%
So the first example is a
square grid or integer--

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:23.390 align:middle line:84%
maybe it's good to
say integer grid.

00:03:23.390 --> 00:03:25.880 align:middle line:84%
So for this example,
let's suppose

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:27.730 align:middle line:90%
that q is actually prime.

00:03:27.730 --> 00:03:31.490 align:middle line:90%


00:03:31.490 --> 00:03:33.960 align:middle line:84%
You can do similar
things if q is not prime.

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:36.530 align:middle line:84%
It's just easier
to write it down.

00:03:36.530 --> 00:03:42.500 align:middle line:84%
So our set X is going to
be the set X1, X2 where

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:46.070 align:middle line:90%
X1 and X2 go between 1 and n.

00:03:46.070 --> 00:03:47.870 align:middle line:84%
So even though we're
over a finite field,

00:03:47.870 --> 00:03:49.915 align:middle line:84%
you can think of this as
a square integer grid.

00:03:49.915 --> 00:03:52.470 align:middle line:90%


00:03:52.470 --> 00:03:54.530 align:middle line:84%
And then we were
saying last time

00:03:54.530 --> 00:03:57.690 align:middle line:84%
that if you take a square
grid, an integer grid,

00:03:57.690 --> 00:03:59.690 align:middle line:84%
and you do a projection
in a direction, that's

00:03:59.690 --> 00:04:04.050 align:middle line:84%
kind of a rational angle, then
you get a small projection.

00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:06.860 align:middle line:84%
So that's what our set of
directions is going to be.

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:13.310 align:middle line:84%
A set of directions is going
to be the set of a1 over a2

00:04:13.310 --> 00:04:20.383 align:middle line:84%
where a1 and a2 go from 1 up to
some A. So N and A parameters

00:04:20.383 --> 00:04:21.300 align:middle line:90%
that we can play with.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:24.140 align:middle line:84%
There are many square
grids, many choices.

00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:24.840 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:27.650 align:middle line:84%
So now let's figure
out what is S of X, D.

00:04:27.650 --> 00:04:33.860 align:middle line:84%
So what happens when I
perform a projection of X

00:04:33.860 --> 00:04:35.990 align:middle line:90%
at one of these angles?

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:42.410 align:middle line:84%
So if theta is in D,
I'm going to take pi

00:04:42.410 --> 00:04:53.620 align:middle line:84%
and if x is in X, so if I
take pi theta of x1, x2,

00:04:53.620 --> 00:05:01.750 align:middle line:84%
then I get x1 plus
a1 over a2 x2.

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:04.280 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to put it
over a common denominator.

00:05:04.280 --> 00:05:11.025 align:middle line:84%
So it's a2 x1 plus
a1 x2 over a2.

00:05:11.025 --> 00:05:13.660 align:middle line:90%


00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:14.180 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:17.560 align:middle line:84%
Now in this situation, we're
imagining that theta is fixed

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:20.690 align:middle line:84%
and we're varying
little x and big X.

00:05:20.690 --> 00:05:23.870 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to try to see
how big is pi theta of big X.

00:05:23.870 --> 00:05:27.080 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to see if a is
fixed, and I vary x1 and x2,

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:29.090 align:middle line:84%
how many different
numbers do I have here?

00:05:29.090 --> 00:05:30.677 align:middle line:84%
So the denominator
isn't important

00:05:30.677 --> 00:05:31.760 align:middle line:90%
because it's not changing.

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:34.190 align:middle line:84%
And I want to know how many
different numerators I have.

00:05:34.190 --> 00:05:37.070 align:middle line:84%
And the numerator is
going to be an integer.

00:05:37.070 --> 00:05:41.270 align:middle line:84%
And it has size a times
n at most plus a times n.

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:43.570 align:middle line:84%
So it basically
has size a times n.

00:05:43.570 --> 00:05:48.340 align:middle line:84%
So we see that the size
of the projection of x

00:05:48.340 --> 00:05:51.280 align:middle line:90%
is at most a times n.

00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:53.530 align:middle line:84%
So this less than
with a squiggle here,

00:05:53.530 --> 00:05:55.880 align:middle line:84%
means there's a constant
factor that I left out here.

00:05:55.880 --> 00:05:57.085 align:middle line:90%
It's a factor of 2.

00:05:57.085 --> 00:05:58.960 align:middle line:84%
But in general, a squiggle
just means there's

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:00.530 align:middle line:90%
some constant factor left out.

00:06:00.530 --> 00:06:03.160 align:middle line:90%


00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:05.150 align:middle line:90%
And S is the biggest of these.

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:18.280 align:middle line:84%
So S of X, D is
around A times N.

00:06:18.280 --> 00:06:22.930 align:middle line:84%
OK, so then you could
do a little algebra

00:06:22.930 --> 00:06:26.920 align:middle line:84%
to see how S and X and
D relate to each other.

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:40.090 align:middle line:84%
And if you do that, you see that
D is around S squared over X.

00:06:40.090 --> 00:06:42.480 align:middle line:84%
So that's how it works
in an integer grid.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:47.530 align:middle line:90%


00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:51.530 align:middle line:84%
And there's one more example
that I thought I would mention,

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:53.090 align:middle line:84%
which we also
mentioned last time.

00:06:53.090 --> 00:06:55.190 align:middle line:84%
It's an example that
comes from subfields.

00:06:55.190 --> 00:07:00.490 align:middle line:84%
So if q is not prime, then Fp
is an interesting subset of Fq,

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:03.570 align:middle line:84%
and Fp squared is an interesting
subset of Fq squared.

00:07:03.570 --> 00:07:10.420 align:middle line:90%


00:07:10.420 --> 00:07:12.660 align:middle line:84%
So this is called
the subfield example.

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:17.620 align:middle line:90%


00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:21.490 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that q is p
squared, or a similar phenomenon

00:07:21.490 --> 00:07:25.330 align:middle line:84%
if q is a higher power of
p, but the computations

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:26.950 align:middle line:90%
are a bit different.

00:07:26.950 --> 00:07:30.400 align:middle line:84%
So if q is p
squared, our set X is

00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:35.290 align:middle line:84%
going to be Fp squared
sitting in Fq squared.

00:07:35.290 --> 00:07:39.220 align:middle line:84%
So the size of X is p
squared, which is q.

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:41.860 align:middle line:84%
And our set of
directions is going

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:44.780 align:middle line:90%
to be Fp which is sitting in Fq.

00:07:44.780 --> 00:07:46.810 align:middle line:84%
So the size of our
set of directions

00:07:46.810 --> 00:07:51.220 align:middle line:90%
is p which is q to the one half.

00:07:51.220 --> 00:08:05.030 align:middle line:84%
And then if theta is in D, and
x1, x2 is in X, pi theta of x1,

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:08.450 align:middle line:90%
x2 is x1 plus x2 theta.

00:08:08.450 --> 00:08:11.320 align:middle line:84%
All those things are
in the subfield Fp.

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:12.740 align:middle line:90%
So this is in Fp.

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:15.340 align:middle line:90%


00:08:15.340 --> 00:08:20.440 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, the size of
pi theta of X is at most p.

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:22.690 align:middle line:90%
In fact exactly p.

00:08:22.690 --> 00:08:37.419 align:middle line:84%
And so that's our S. And this
example coming from subfields

00:08:37.419 --> 00:08:40.840 align:middle line:84%
is more extreme than the
example coming from grids.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:45.040 align:middle line:84%
So if you were to take this
value of X And this value of S,

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:50.960 align:middle line:84%
and plug them in here to make
a fair comparison, in the grids

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:53.980 align:middle line:84%
we would have only one
direction if we did that,

00:08:53.980 --> 00:08:56.230 align:middle line:84%
but here we have
many directions.

00:08:56.230 --> 00:08:59.770 align:middle line:84%
So this thing has
very small projections

00:08:59.770 --> 00:09:02.655 align:middle line:84%
in many different directions,
even more so than a square grid.

00:09:02.655 --> 00:09:14.512 align:middle line:90%


00:09:14.512 --> 00:09:15.983 align:middle line:90%
So those are a few examples.

00:09:15.983 --> 00:09:21.860 align:middle line:90%


00:09:21.860 --> 00:09:25.330 align:middle line:84%
And based on that, I can
tell you a conjecture

00:09:25.330 --> 00:09:27.170 align:middle line:90%
that we stated also last time.

00:09:27.170 --> 00:09:29.260 align:middle line:84%
And also, I can tell
you some of the things

00:09:29.260 --> 00:09:31.860 align:middle line:84%
we know about this conjecture,
some of the main results.

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:36.010 align:middle line:90%


00:09:36.010 --> 00:09:39.820 align:middle line:84%
So first, I'll say
the conjecture,

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:48.970 align:middle line:84%
so if q equals p which is
prime and we're in this setup.

00:09:48.970 --> 00:09:54.790 align:middle line:84%
And S is smaller
than around X over 2,

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:57.690 align:middle line:84%
then we can't do better
than the square grid.

00:09:57.690 --> 00:10:06.310 align:middle line:90%


00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:10.420 align:middle line:84%
So let's explain all the
hypotheses in this conjecture.

00:10:10.420 --> 00:10:13.040 align:middle line:90%
So why do we have this?

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:17.140 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you take
any set D S of X,

00:10:17.140 --> 00:10:21.610 align:middle line:84%
D is obviously smaller
than the size of X.

00:10:21.610 --> 00:10:23.890 align:middle line:84%
So if S was allowed
to be the size of X

00:10:23.890 --> 00:10:25.670 align:middle line:90%
then D could be everything.

00:10:25.670 --> 00:10:28.930 align:middle line:84%
And there would be no
meaningful upper bound on D.

00:10:28.930 --> 00:10:32.650 align:middle line:84%
So we have to insist that it's
somewhat smaller than that.

00:10:32.650 --> 00:10:35.890 align:middle line:84%
You could ask about the
range in between here and X,

00:10:35.890 --> 00:10:39.460 align:middle line:84%
there's something to say but
I think not super interesting.

00:10:39.460 --> 00:10:42.400 align:middle line:90%
So we'll look at this version.

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:44.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:44.020 --> 00:10:45.650 align:middle line:90%
We have this set up.

00:10:45.650 --> 00:10:48.770 align:middle line:84%
And why do we also add
here that q is a prime?

00:10:48.770 --> 00:10:51.650 align:middle line:84%
Well, we have to add that
because of example two.

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:53.557 align:middle line:84%
If q is not a prime,
you have that example.

00:10:53.557 --> 00:10:55.015 align:middle line:84%
And we just saw
that this is false.

00:10:55.015 --> 00:10:57.640 align:middle line:90%


00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:00.040 align:middle line:84%
And this conjecture is
plausible in the sense

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:03.100 align:middle line:84%
that there's no counterexample,
that no one has found an example

00:11:03.100 --> 00:11:04.940 align:middle line:90%
that beats the square grid.

00:11:04.940 --> 00:11:07.330 align:middle line:84%
And basically, no one
has found an example that

00:11:07.330 --> 00:11:12.458 align:middle line:84%
even is, well, OK, there
are very few examples that

00:11:12.458 --> 00:11:14.000 align:middle line:84%
are competitive with
the square grid,

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:15.800 align:middle line:84%
and they're all small
variations on it.

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:20.170 align:middle line:90%


00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:24.880 align:middle line:84%
You also might wonder what
happens if q is not a prime.

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:29.470 align:middle line:84%
And I haven't seen anyone write
down a conjecture for that.

00:11:29.470 --> 00:11:31.900 align:middle line:84%
I think, roughly speaking,
what people believe

00:11:31.900 --> 00:11:35.560 align:middle line:84%
is that all of the
interesting examples

00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:38.210 align:middle line:84%
should be of this
type or that type,

00:11:38.210 --> 00:11:40.000 align:middle line:84%
or maybe you can combine
them a little bit

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.860 align:middle line:90%
by taking a grid of subfields.

00:11:44.860 --> 00:11:47.500 align:middle line:84%
So it would be a
reasonable little project

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:51.100 align:middle line:84%
if anyone is interested to try
to write down the known examples

00:11:51.100 --> 00:11:53.040 align:middle line:84%
and make a conjecture
about what happens.

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:55.600 align:middle line:90%


00:11:55.600 --> 00:11:58.300 align:middle line:84%
All right, now this
conjecture is open.

00:11:58.300 --> 00:12:00.830 align:middle line:84%
But let's start to talk
about what we know.

00:12:00.830 --> 00:12:03.130 align:middle line:84%
Well, I'm going to state
some theorems for you

00:12:03.130 --> 00:12:04.730 align:middle line:90%
and we'll prove the theorems.

00:12:04.730 --> 00:12:07.060 align:middle line:84%
And maybe more importantly
we'll introduce

00:12:07.060 --> 00:12:11.080 align:middle line:84%
some of the basic techniques
in projection theory.

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:14.390 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to talk
about two techniques today.

00:12:14.390 --> 00:12:17.290 align:middle line:84%
One of them is a
double-counting argument that

00:12:17.290 --> 00:12:19.160 align:middle line:90%
has a combinatorics flavor.

00:12:19.160 --> 00:12:22.060 align:middle line:84%
And the other is a
Fourier analytic argument

00:12:22.060 --> 00:12:24.610 align:middle line:90%
that's based on orthogonality.

00:12:24.610 --> 00:12:27.730 align:middle line:90%
And this is what they give.

00:12:27.730 --> 00:12:35.350 align:middle line:84%
So theorem one which is
based on double counting,

00:12:35.350 --> 00:12:46.540 align:middle line:84%
say if we're in this setup and
S is smaller than X over 2,

00:12:46.540 --> 00:13:06.796 align:middle line:84%
then the number of directions
is smaller than around S.

00:13:06.796 --> 00:13:11.603 align:middle line:84%
Now, if S is around X over
2, this is actually sharp.

00:13:11.603 --> 00:13:14.790 align:middle line:90%


00:13:14.790 --> 00:13:15.290 align:middle line:90%
Hold on.

00:13:15.290 --> 00:13:16.832 align:middle line:84%
Let me look at my
notes for a second.

00:13:16.832 --> 00:13:24.790 align:middle line:90%


00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:26.485 align:middle line:84%
OK, actually I wrote
that in my notes,

00:13:26.485 --> 00:13:27.860 align:middle line:84%
but I'm not quite
sure it's true.

00:13:27.860 --> 00:13:29.818 align:middle line:84%
Let's just go on and I'll
tell you theorem two.

00:13:29.818 --> 00:13:33.520 align:middle line:90%


00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:35.890 align:middle line:84%
So theorem 2 is
based on what I'll

00:13:35.890 --> 00:13:38.380 align:middle line:84%
call a Fourier method,
or orthogonality,

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:39.660 align:middle line:90%
or something like that.

00:13:39.660 --> 00:13:43.560 align:middle line:84%
It says, if we have
this setup and this time

00:13:43.560 --> 00:13:48.810 align:middle line:84%
if we suppose that's S
is smaller than q over 2,

00:13:48.810 --> 00:13:58.580 align:middle line:84%
then D is smaller
than S times q over X.

00:13:58.580 --> 00:14:03.030 align:middle line:84%
So let's digest this
statement a little bit.

00:14:03.030 --> 00:14:06.880 align:middle line:84%
So the projection is
always a subset of Fq.

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:09.840 align:middle line:84%
So S is always smaller
than or equal to q.

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:13.650 align:middle line:84%
So this hypothesis says that
it's significantly smaller

00:14:13.650 --> 00:14:14.260 align:middle line:90%
than that.

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:18.100 align:middle line:84%
The projection is significantly
smaller than the whole space OK.

00:14:18.100 --> 00:14:21.360 align:middle line:84%
And then we get this
bound, and this bound

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:24.000 align:middle line:84%
is the most interesting
in the case S was actually

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:25.740 align:middle line:90%
close to q over 2.

00:14:25.740 --> 00:14:30.160 align:middle line:84%
Because in that case this q And
this S are about the same size.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:32.700 align:middle line:84%
So this is around
S squared over X,

00:14:32.700 --> 00:14:37.110 align:middle line:90%
which matches the grid example.

00:14:37.110 --> 00:14:41.760 align:middle line:90%
So this is actually sharp.

00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:45.460 align:middle line:90%
if S is around q over 2.

00:14:45.460 --> 00:14:49.320 align:middle line:90%


00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:51.740 align:middle line:84%
OK, I find that quite
striking and impressive.

00:14:51.740 --> 00:14:52.740 align:middle line:90%
This is a great example.

00:14:52.740 --> 00:14:54.840 align:middle line:84%
It has an interesting
intricate structure.

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:56.880 align:middle line:84%
And we're wondering
whether it was sharp

00:14:56.880 --> 00:15:00.300 align:middle line:84%
and at least in this
one regime, this theorem

00:15:00.300 --> 00:15:03.420 align:middle line:90%
shows that it actually is sharp.

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:06.430 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, S could
be a lot smaller than q.

00:15:06.430 --> 00:15:08.340 align:middle line:84%
Then we get some
bound here and we

00:15:08.340 --> 00:15:14.310 align:middle line:84%
don't have any example
that matches that bound.

00:15:14.310 --> 00:15:17.500 align:middle line:84%
I guess I should also say
this works over any field.

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:20.450 align:middle line:84%
So if you plug-in example
two it's actually also sharp.

00:15:20.450 --> 00:15:23.580 align:middle line:90%


00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:25.955 align:middle line:84%
And so it's also
sharp in example two.

00:15:25.955 --> 00:15:33.020 align:middle line:90%


00:15:33.020 --> 00:15:33.520 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:35.648 align:middle line:84%
But there are a bunch of
choices of the parameter.

00:15:35.648 --> 00:15:37.940 align:middle line:84%
You could make where it's
not clear that this is sharp.

00:15:37.940 --> 00:15:43.740 align:middle line:90%


00:15:43.740 --> 00:15:45.990 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the big goal
of the class is

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:47.980 align:middle line:84%
to introduce these
two techniques really.

00:15:47.980 --> 00:15:50.673 align:middle line:84%
And we'll use them to
prove these two theorems.

00:15:50.673 --> 00:15:52.590 align:middle line:84%
But maybe it's a good
place to pause and check

00:15:52.590 --> 00:15:54.900 align:middle line:84%
if people have
questions or comments.

00:15:54.900 --> 00:15:56.185 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:15:56.185 --> 00:15:57.810 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: In the
first theorem, are you

00:15:57.810 --> 00:15:59.340 align:middle line:90%
assuming that it's prime?

00:15:59.340 --> 00:16:03.540 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: We are not
assuming that it's prime.

00:16:03.540 --> 00:16:05.540 align:middle line:90%
Right, that's right.

00:16:05.540 --> 00:16:07.540 align:middle line:84%
We're not assuming it's
prime in either theorem.

00:16:07.540 --> 00:16:11.290 align:middle line:84%
And so where it says setup
it means we're assuming this.

00:16:11.290 --> 00:16:11.790 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:16:11.790 --> 00:16:13.050 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:16:13.050 --> 00:16:15.090 align:middle line:84%
And so that raises
a point that it

00:16:15.090 --> 00:16:17.880 align:middle line:84%
appears that the true
answer to this question

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:20.470 align:middle line:84%
depends on whether q
is prime or not prime.

00:16:20.470 --> 00:16:24.010 align:middle line:84%
But neither of these
techniques depend on that.

00:16:24.010 --> 00:16:26.250 align:middle line:84%
They work for all
q, and they're not

00:16:26.250 --> 00:16:28.660 align:middle line:84%
able to notice whether
q is prime or not prime.

00:16:28.660 --> 00:16:30.160 align:middle line:84%
That will eventually
be a big theme.

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:32.077 align:middle line:84%
We won't get to it today,
but eventually we'll

00:16:32.077 --> 00:16:34.800 align:middle line:84%
try to find some techniques that
do notice whether q is prime

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:38.582 align:middle line:90%
or not prime Yeah?

00:16:38.582 --> 00:16:40.290 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: For the
premise, S is less than

00:16:40.290 --> 00:16:42.840 align:middle line:84%
or equal to the size
of X divided by 2,

00:16:42.840 --> 00:16:45.883 align:middle line:84%
how easy is it to construct
other examples that satisfy

00:16:45.883 --> 00:16:46.925 align:middle line:90%
that element of the grid?

00:16:46.925 --> 00:16:50.200 align:middle line:90%


00:16:50.200 --> 00:16:50.950 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:16:50.950 --> 00:17:01.830 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, how
many examples can we

00:17:01.830 --> 00:17:04.829 align:middle line:84%
find which obey the hypotheses,
so this theorem says anything

00:17:04.829 --> 00:17:06.990 align:middle line:90%
about them?

00:17:06.990 --> 00:17:09.960 align:middle line:84%
Well, I think it's not
super hard because we're

00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:11.705 align:middle line:90%
allowed to take D to be small.

00:17:11.705 --> 00:17:21.100 align:middle line:90%


00:17:21.100 --> 00:17:24.599 align:middle line:84%
So if D is just one
direction, then you

00:17:24.599 --> 00:17:27.599 align:middle line:84%
could easily arrange the points
so that their projection in one

00:17:27.599 --> 00:17:29.140 align:middle line:90%
direction is quite small.

00:17:29.140 --> 00:17:31.330 align:middle line:84%
And you have a lot more
flexibility than a grid.

00:17:31.330 --> 00:17:35.310 align:middle line:84%
And if you'd like the projection
to be small in two directions,

00:17:35.310 --> 00:17:39.100 align:middle line:84%
then you would want some
kind of Cartesian product,

00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:41.850 align:middle line:84%
but there's still a lot
more Cartesian products

00:17:41.850 --> 00:17:43.620 align:middle line:90%
than integer grids.

00:17:43.620 --> 00:17:46.350 align:middle line:84%
And then as you add more
directions, it gets more rigid

00:17:46.350 --> 00:17:48.760 align:middle line:84%
and we can start
to think about it.

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:50.650 align:middle line:90%
We can think about it later on.

00:17:50.650 --> 00:17:54.180 align:middle line:84%
It's a neat question how many
examples we can come up with.

00:17:54.180 --> 00:17:55.890 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:17:55.890 --> 00:17:58.860 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:17:58.860 --> 00:18:00.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:01.600 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:04.200 align:middle line:90%


00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:09.770 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: In the example why
you said q equals p prime.

00:18:09.770 --> 00:18:12.796 align:middle line:90%
Can be p be a prime?

00:18:12.796 --> 00:18:15.060 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]

00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:17.640 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yes, right.

00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:19.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:19.590 --> 00:18:22.290 align:middle line:84%
So the question was
up in example one,

00:18:22.290 --> 00:18:24.480 align:middle line:90%
we assume that q is prime.

00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:27.170 align:middle line:84%
Are there examples similar
to that if q is not prime?

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:30.120 align:middle line:90%


00:18:30.120 --> 00:18:33.210 align:middle line:84%
So if N and A are smaller,
if q is p to the r

00:18:33.210 --> 00:18:34.960 align:middle line:84%
and you choose N and
A smaller than p,

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:38.340 align:middle line:84%
you can just use what's
on the board verbatim.

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:41.080 align:middle line:84%
If you wanted to choose
N and A bigger than p,

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:44.910 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't really
make sense in Fq.

00:18:44.910 --> 00:18:46.745 align:middle line:84%
So I think that
there's a fix for that.

00:18:46.745 --> 00:18:48.870 align:middle line:84%
But I didn't have time to
think through the details

00:18:48.870 --> 00:18:49.640 align:middle line:90%
before class.

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:57.390 align:middle line:90%


00:18:57.390 --> 00:19:01.325 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, so homework for one of us.

00:19:01.325 --> 00:19:06.000 align:middle line:90%


00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:06.700 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:06.700 --> 00:19:09.000 align:middle line:84%
So let's start
proving some things.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.570 align:middle line:84%
So first we'll do
the double counting.

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:23.700 align:middle line:90%


00:19:23.700 --> 00:19:28.080 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that you just
look at one direction

00:19:28.080 --> 00:19:30.100 align:middle line:90%
where this projection is small.

00:19:30.100 --> 00:19:34.380 align:middle line:84%
If S is a lot smaller than X, it
will look something like this.

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:38.670 align:middle line:84%
So here is the space
we're projecting onto

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:41.353 align:middle line:90%
and we'll have some points.

00:19:41.353 --> 00:19:43.920 align:middle line:90%


00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:45.820 align:middle line:90%
And this is our projection map.

00:19:45.820 --> 00:19:48.660 align:middle line:84%
So here, we have
X, and this arrow

00:19:48.660 --> 00:19:52.980 align:middle line:90%
is the projection map pi theta.

00:19:52.980 --> 00:20:00.850 align:middle line:84%
And then down here we
have pi theta of X. OK.

00:20:00.850 --> 00:20:03.210 align:middle line:84%
And you'll notice that for
each point in the projection

00:20:03.210 --> 00:20:05.550 align:middle line:84%
or at least for most
points in the projection,

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:10.080 align:middle line:84%
we will have many points of X
that are going on top of it.

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:12.804 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:12.804 --> 00:20:16.050 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to pay
attention to that.

00:20:16.050 --> 00:20:21.930 align:middle line:84%
And the first thing we'll
say is that if S is smaller

00:20:21.930 --> 00:20:25.380 align:middle line:84%
than x over 2, then we
have a lot of points

00:20:25.380 --> 00:20:28.620 align:middle line:90%
going on top of each other.

00:20:28.620 --> 00:20:33.450 align:middle line:84%
So for every theta in
our set of directions,

00:20:33.450 --> 00:20:38.580 align:middle line:84%
the number of pairs x1
and x2 in X that got

00:20:38.580 --> 00:20:40.205 align:middle line:90%
projected to the same point.

00:20:40.205 --> 00:20:45.030 align:middle line:90%


00:20:45.030 --> 00:20:54.030 align:middle line:84%
That should be at least around
S times X over S squared.

00:20:54.030 --> 00:20:55.653 align:middle line:90%
OK, so let's digest that.

00:20:55.653 --> 00:20:57.820 align:middle line:84%
First of all, I'll warn you
that I changed notation.

00:20:57.820 --> 00:21:01.240 align:middle line:84%
So x1 and x2 are
each points in X.

00:21:01.240 --> 00:21:05.200 align:middle line:84%
Those are not the
components of anything.

00:21:05.200 --> 00:21:07.000 align:middle line:90%
And so why is this?

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:12.420 align:middle line:84%
Well imagine first that
each point in the projection

00:21:12.420 --> 00:21:14.760 align:middle line:84%
has the same number
of preimages.

00:21:14.760 --> 00:21:17.250 align:middle line:84%
So each of these
points has about X

00:21:17.250 --> 00:21:21.660 align:middle line:84%
over S points of X
sitting above it.

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:25.620 align:middle line:84%
And then the number of
ways to choose two of them

00:21:25.620 --> 00:21:29.340 align:middle line:90%
would be X over S squared.

00:21:29.340 --> 00:21:31.840 align:middle line:84%
And that would be true for
each of these S points.

00:21:31.840 --> 00:21:35.700 align:middle line:90%
So that would give us this.

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:37.680 align:middle line:84%
Now actually, let
me add here that I'm

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:40.610 align:middle line:84%
interested in two different
points that got projected

00:21:40.610 --> 00:21:41.360 align:middle line:90%
to the same point.

00:21:41.360 --> 00:21:44.640 align:middle line:90%


00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:45.940 align:middle line:90%
So this is still true.

00:21:45.940 --> 00:21:48.070 align:middle line:84%
But because I put two
different points here,

00:21:48.070 --> 00:21:50.846 align:middle line:84%
that's where I needed
to use this hypothesis.

00:21:50.846 --> 00:21:53.700 align:middle line:90%


00:21:53.700 --> 00:21:56.520 align:middle line:84%
So that was some intuition
why it might be true.

00:21:56.520 --> 00:21:58.170 align:middle line:84%
Then you might
wonder, well, maybe

00:21:58.170 --> 00:21:59.500 align:middle line:90%
they're not evenly distributed.

00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:02.170 align:middle line:84%
Maybe some of these points have
more preimages than others.

00:22:02.170 --> 00:22:04.450 align:middle line:84%
It turns out that
that only helps you.

00:22:04.450 --> 00:22:06.100 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to make
it an exercise.

00:22:06.100 --> 00:22:08.920 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of a standard
combinatorics exercise.

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:10.650 align:middle line:84%
So it's exercise on
your first problem

00:22:10.650 --> 00:22:13.570 align:middle line:90%
set using Cauchy-Schwarz.

00:22:13.570 --> 00:22:25.620 align:middle line:90%


00:22:25.620 --> 00:22:26.120 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:22:26.120 --> 00:22:28.820 align:middle line:84%
So there are a lot of points
getting collapsed together

00:22:28.820 --> 00:22:30.562 align:middle line:84%
in these different
projections, and we're

00:22:30.562 --> 00:22:31.770 align:middle line:90%
going to put it all together.

00:22:31.770 --> 00:22:33.290 align:middle line:84%
So the key object
that we're going

00:22:33.290 --> 00:22:39.320 align:middle line:84%
to count is the number
of directions theta

00:22:39.320 --> 00:22:45.920 align:middle line:84%
and distinct points
in X, so that they

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:47.190 align:middle line:90%
have the same projection.

00:22:47.190 --> 00:22:51.500 align:middle line:90%


00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:53.420 align:middle line:84%
And there have to
be a lot of those

00:22:53.420 --> 00:22:55.620 align:middle line:84%
because for every direction
there are a lot of them.

00:22:55.620 --> 00:23:00.650 align:middle line:84%
So the number of these is at
least X squared S inverse number

00:23:00.650 --> 00:23:01.530 align:middle line:90%
of directions.

00:23:01.530 --> 00:23:04.370 align:middle line:84%
The X squared S inverse
is just that simplified.

00:23:04.370 --> 00:23:06.690 align:middle line:84%
And that was how many there
are in each direction.

00:23:06.690 --> 00:23:08.070 align:middle line:90%
And there are D directions.

00:23:08.070 --> 00:23:14.852 align:middle line:90%


00:23:14.852 --> 00:23:20.450 align:middle line:84%
So now the point is that it's
hard to have this many collapses

00:23:20.450 --> 00:23:24.090 align:middle line:84%
because if you take any
two pairs of points in X,

00:23:24.090 --> 00:23:26.510 align:middle line:84%
there is only one direction
in which they get mapped

00:23:26.510 --> 00:23:29.450 align:middle line:90%
on top of each other.

00:23:29.450 --> 00:23:34.510 align:middle line:84%
So that gives us an
upper bound on this star.

00:23:34.510 --> 00:23:41.580 align:middle line:84%
But for any points x1 not equal
to x2, the number of theta

00:23:41.580 --> 00:23:49.310 align:middle line:84%
so that pi theta of x1
equals pi theta of x2,

00:23:49.310 --> 00:23:51.020 align:middle line:90%
there's at most one.

00:23:51.020 --> 00:23:53.690 align:middle line:84%
And that gives us an
upper bound for star.

00:23:53.690 --> 00:23:59.480 align:middle line:84%
Star is upper
bounded by x squared.

00:23:59.480 --> 00:24:01.430 align:middle line:84%
Once you choose
x1 and x2, there's

00:24:01.430 --> 00:24:02.620 align:middle line:90%
only one choice of theta.

00:24:02.620 --> 00:24:10.950 align:middle line:90%


00:24:10.950 --> 00:24:14.240 align:middle line:84%
So this key quantity is
sandwiched in between here

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:22.010 align:middle line:84%
and here we have X squared S
inverse D is less than star,

00:24:22.010 --> 00:24:25.370 align:middle line:90%
is less than x squared.

00:24:25.370 --> 00:24:27.290 align:middle line:84%
And you simplify
this a little bit.

00:24:27.290 --> 00:24:31.930 align:middle line:84%
And we get that D is less
than S. And that's the proof.

00:24:31.930 --> 00:24:49.790 align:middle line:90%


00:24:49.790 --> 00:24:52.490 align:middle line:84%
Let me summarize it
without the equations.

00:24:52.490 --> 00:24:55.610 align:middle line:84%
The key object is
this object, star.

00:24:55.610 --> 00:24:59.220 align:middle line:84%
Let's call let's call this
the set of coincidences.

00:24:59.220 --> 00:25:01.490 align:middle line:84%
A coincidence is when
you have two points in X

00:25:01.490 --> 00:25:05.720 align:middle line:84%
that get mapped to the
same point by pi theta.

00:25:05.720 --> 00:25:08.160 align:middle line:84%
And if many
projections are small,

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:10.490 align:middle line:90%
there must be many coincidences.

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:12.290 align:middle line:84%
But there can't be that
many because if you

00:25:12.290 --> 00:25:15.440 align:middle line:84%
take two points, x1 and x2,
there's only one direction that

00:25:15.440 --> 00:25:16.530 align:middle line:90%
makes a coincidence.

00:25:16.530 --> 00:25:17.697 align:middle line:90%
And that's what we're using.

00:25:17.697 --> 00:25:28.946 align:middle line:90%


00:25:28.946 --> 00:25:31.600 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
about double counting?

00:25:31.600 --> 00:25:38.900 align:middle line:90%


00:25:38.900 --> 00:25:40.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:40.010 --> 00:25:42.500 align:middle line:84%
Let me show you the
second approach, which

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:45.770 align:middle line:84%
is based on I called
it a Fourier approach,

00:25:45.770 --> 00:25:50.900 align:middle line:84%
or based on orthogonality,
or based on cancelation.

00:25:50.900 --> 00:25:53.720 align:middle line:84%
So this approach
begins with an image

00:25:53.720 --> 00:25:57.170 align:middle line:84%
that I want you to have
in mind, and that we

00:25:57.170 --> 00:26:00.110 align:middle line:84%
could try to work on
this image in many ways.

00:26:00.110 --> 00:26:02.290 align:middle line:84%
So it's the overlapping
lines image.

00:26:02.290 --> 00:26:05.810 align:middle line:90%


00:26:05.810 --> 00:26:08.870 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I have
a bunch of points

00:26:08.870 --> 00:26:13.880 align:middle line:84%
that have small projections
in many directions.

00:26:13.880 --> 00:26:17.436 align:middle line:84%
So if I project this down,
it has a small projection.

00:26:17.436 --> 00:26:23.210 align:middle line:90%


00:26:23.210 --> 00:26:25.860 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I'll call
this pi theta 1.

00:26:25.860 --> 00:26:28.890 align:middle line:84%
If I look at the
preimages of these,

00:26:28.890 --> 00:26:35.140 align:middle line:84%
I'll get some lines
in a certain direction

00:26:35.140 --> 00:26:37.250 align:middle line:90%
that corresponds to theta 1.

00:26:37.250 --> 00:26:41.310 align:middle line:84%
And so I've covered my set
with not too many lines.

00:26:41.310 --> 00:26:43.940 align:middle line:84%
So down here there
are at most S points.

00:26:43.940 --> 00:26:47.550 align:middle line:84%
So over here we have
at most S lines.

00:26:47.550 --> 00:26:50.725 align:middle line:84%
And I'll call this set
of lines L theta 1.

00:26:50.725 --> 00:26:54.530 align:middle line:90%


00:26:54.530 --> 00:27:05.400 align:middle line:84%
So to summarize, if pi theta of
X is less than or equal to S,

00:27:05.400 --> 00:27:17.450 align:middle line:84%
then I get a set called L theta
is a set of at most S lines that

00:27:17.450 --> 00:27:21.080 align:middle line:84%
are I guess
perpendicular to theta,

00:27:21.080 --> 00:27:25.525 align:middle line:90%
and that they cover my set x.

00:27:25.525 --> 00:27:29.150 align:middle line:90%


00:27:29.150 --> 00:27:31.500 align:middle line:84%
So now if I have many
small projections,

00:27:31.500 --> 00:27:33.240 align:middle line:84%
I can do this in
many directions.

00:27:33.240 --> 00:27:36.480 align:middle line:84%
And so I'll have sets of
lines in different directions.

00:27:36.480 --> 00:27:39.170 align:middle line:90%
And I'll cover X many times.

00:27:39.170 --> 00:27:48.065 align:middle line:84%
So I can do this for every
theta in my set of directions.

00:27:48.065 --> 00:27:50.300 align:middle line:90%
So I'll do one more.

00:27:50.300 --> 00:27:52.680 align:middle line:84%
I was meaning to bring some
colored chalk, but I didn't.

00:27:52.680 --> 00:27:56.390 align:middle line:84%
I don't have colored chalk
today, so I'll do my best.

00:27:56.390 --> 00:27:59.420 align:middle line:84%
So let's say this is
a dotted direction.

00:27:59.420 --> 00:28:06.985 align:middle line:84%
And when I project in the theta
2 direction, we have this.

00:28:06.985 --> 00:28:13.220 align:middle line:90%


00:28:13.220 --> 00:28:17.750 align:middle line:84%
So this would be L
theta 2 in dotted lines.

00:28:17.750 --> 00:28:20.250 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not going to add any
more directions to the picture,

00:28:20.250 --> 00:28:23.190 align:middle line:84%
but in your imagination,
imagine that this set of points,

00:28:23.190 --> 00:28:25.940 align:middle line:84%
there are lines going
many different ways that

00:28:25.940 --> 00:28:28.555 align:middle line:90%
are covering the set of points.

00:28:28.555 --> 00:28:31.280 align:middle line:90%


00:28:31.280 --> 00:28:33.860 align:middle line:84%
So in our second method,
and maybe in a lot of things

00:28:33.860 --> 00:28:36.860 align:middle line:84%
that we do, we're going
to imagine these lines

00:28:36.860 --> 00:28:39.440 align:middle line:84%
and work with these lines
as a way of understanding

00:28:39.440 --> 00:28:41.100 align:middle line:90%
the projection estimates.

00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:46.815 align:middle line:90%


00:28:46.815 --> 00:28:49.735 align:middle line:84%
So let me add a little
vocabulary about this.

00:28:49.735 --> 00:28:53.090 align:middle line:90%


00:28:53.090 --> 00:28:56.630 align:middle line:90%
So we've defined L theta.

00:28:56.630 --> 00:28:59.150 align:middle line:84%
L, out whole set of
lines is the union

00:28:59.150 --> 00:29:02.250 align:middle line:84%
over all the different
directions of the lines L theta.

00:29:02.250 --> 00:29:05.240 align:middle line:90%
So that's a set of lines.

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:12.050 align:middle line:84%
And so if L is a line,
I'm going to write

00:29:12.050 --> 00:29:16.190 align:middle line:84%
L of x as an abbreviation for
the characteristic function

00:29:16.190 --> 00:29:20.330 align:middle line:90%
of that line 1 sub L of x

00:29:20.330 --> 00:29:23.000 align:middle line:84%
And we think about what
happens when we add up all

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:24.810 align:middle line:90%
these characteristic functions.

00:29:24.810 --> 00:29:30.440 align:middle line:84%
So f of x is the sum
over all the lines

00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:33.580 align:middle line:90%
in my set of lines, of L of x.

00:29:33.580 --> 00:29:39.170 align:middle line:90%


00:29:39.170 --> 00:29:41.030 align:middle line:84%
So take a moment
to visualize that.

00:29:41.030 --> 00:29:44.960 align:middle line:84%
I have lines going in
different directions.

00:29:44.960 --> 00:29:49.395 align:middle line:84%
Imagine their characteristic
functions and add them all up.

00:29:49.395 --> 00:29:51.270 align:middle line:84%
So when I add them all
up at any given point,

00:29:51.270 --> 00:29:52.937 align:middle line:84%
it will tell me how
many different lines

00:29:52.937 --> 00:29:56.990 align:middle line:84%
to my set of lines went
through that point.

00:29:56.990 --> 00:30:03.200 align:middle line:84%
And so if X is in my set
of points, then f of x

00:30:03.200 --> 00:30:06.260 align:middle line:90%
is the number of directions.

00:30:06.260 --> 00:30:08.510 align:middle line:84%
If I take a point in
my set, this point

00:30:08.510 --> 00:30:11.990 align:middle line:84%
is going to lie in one
line in every direction.

00:30:11.990 --> 00:30:15.110 align:middle line:84%
If I take a point
that's not in my set,

00:30:15.110 --> 00:30:18.143 align:middle line:84%
it's not very clear
what's going to happen.

00:30:18.143 --> 00:30:19.560 align:middle line:84%
Obviously it will
be in any lines,

00:30:19.560 --> 00:30:21.478 align:middle line:90%
but it might be in some lines.

00:30:21.478 --> 00:30:24.020 align:middle line:84%
We don't know much about what
f is doing at those points that

00:30:24.020 --> 00:30:27.900 align:middle line:90%
are not in my set X. OK, great.

00:30:27.900 --> 00:30:30.780 align:middle line:90%


00:30:30.780 --> 00:30:33.560 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to get
at projection theory

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:35.490 align:middle line:84%
by trying to study
this function,

00:30:35.490 --> 00:30:38.090 align:middle line:84%
and in particular, trying
to study the set where

00:30:38.090 --> 00:30:39.570 align:middle line:90%
the function is big.

00:30:39.570 --> 00:30:42.140 align:middle line:84%
So that's going to be
our second approach.

00:30:42.140 --> 00:30:45.350 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to study the
set where this function is big

00:30:45.350 --> 00:30:49.350 align:middle line:84%
using Fourier analysis
and/or using orthogonality.

00:30:49.350 --> 00:31:20.410 align:middle line:90%


00:31:20.410 --> 00:31:21.890 align:middle line:90%
So orthogonality.

00:31:21.890 --> 00:31:30.280 align:middle line:90%


00:31:30.280 --> 00:31:33.250 align:middle line:84%
So L of x are numbers, the
characteristic function

00:31:33.250 --> 00:31:34.420 align:middle line:90%
of a line.

00:31:34.420 --> 00:31:37.140 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to
decompose it into pieces.

00:31:37.140 --> 00:31:40.480 align:middle line:90%


00:31:40.480 --> 00:31:43.070 align:middle line:90%
So there are q points in a line.

00:31:43.070 --> 00:31:45.910 align:middle line:84%
And there are q squared
points in my whole plane.

00:31:45.910 --> 00:31:51.760 align:middle line:84%
And so the average value
of L of x is 1 over q

00:31:51.760 --> 00:31:54.190 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to separate that out.

00:31:54.190 --> 00:32:00.170 align:middle line:84%
That's 1 over q plus a piece
that I'll call L sub high of x.

00:32:00.170 --> 00:32:01.220 align:middle line:90%
That h is for high.

00:32:01.220 --> 00:32:03.700 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about that
name more in a sec.

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:10.430 align:middle line:84%
So this is the average
value of our function.

00:32:10.430 --> 00:32:19.190 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, the
leftover piece has mean 0,

00:32:19.190 --> 00:32:23.620 align:middle line:84%
it has average
value 0, has mean 0.

00:32:23.620 --> 00:32:28.030 align:middle line:84%
And I also will think of this
as the zero frequency piece

00:32:28.030 --> 00:32:31.960 align:middle line:84%
and the high frequency piece
in terms of Fourier analysis.

00:32:31.960 --> 00:32:33.050 align:middle line:90%
We can make that precise.

00:32:33.050 --> 00:32:34.425 align:middle line:84%
We'll do that a
little bit later.

00:32:34.425 --> 00:32:36.823 align:middle line:90%


00:32:36.823 --> 00:32:38.740 align:middle line:84%
Depending on how much
Fourier analysis you do,

00:32:38.740 --> 00:32:40.930 align:middle line:84%
you may or may not
like this intuition.

00:32:40.930 --> 00:32:44.200 align:middle line:84%
But this is a constant part,
and this is a higher frequency

00:32:44.200 --> 00:32:47.030 align:middle line:90%
oscillating part OK.

00:32:47.030 --> 00:32:48.140 align:middle line:90%
Those are just words.

00:32:48.140 --> 00:32:50.830 align:middle line:90%
So we decompose it like this.

00:32:50.830 --> 00:33:00.790 align:middle line:84%
Now the key observation
is that, oversimplifying

00:33:00.790 --> 00:33:04.120 align:middle line:84%
just a little bit, these
high frequency parts

00:33:04.120 --> 00:33:06.400 align:middle line:90%
are orthogonal to each other.

00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:08.500 align:middle line:90%
So here's a precise statement.

00:33:08.500 --> 00:33:13.960 align:middle line:84%
So if L1 not equal
to L2, are lines,

00:33:13.960 --> 00:33:15.880 align:middle line:90%
we have two different lines.

00:33:15.880 --> 00:33:20.890 align:middle line:84%
Then the sum over
all of the points

00:33:20.890 --> 00:33:28.995 align:middle line:84%
in the plane of L1 h of x, L2 h
of x is less than or equal to 0.

00:33:28.995 --> 00:33:32.770 align:middle line:90%


00:33:32.770 --> 00:33:35.660 align:middle line:84%
Now when we prove this
lemma in a little bit,

00:33:35.660 --> 00:33:39.020 align:middle line:84%
we will see that it's
almost always equal to 0.

00:33:39.020 --> 00:33:41.878 align:middle line:84%
So these functions are
almost always orthogonal.

00:33:41.878 --> 00:33:43.670 align:middle line:84%
And once in a while
they're not orthogonal.

00:33:43.670 --> 00:33:44.750 align:middle line:90%
But then it's negative.

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:47.170 align:middle line:84%
That part isn't that
important anyway.

00:33:47.170 --> 00:33:51.520 align:middle line:84%
So roughly speaking, these
functions L1h and L2h

00:33:51.520 --> 00:33:53.500 align:middle line:90%
are orthogonal.

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:55.845 align:middle line:90%
Now how does that help us?

00:33:55.845 --> 00:33:58.570 align:middle line:90%


00:33:58.570 --> 00:34:03.370 align:middle line:90%
Well let's think about f of x.

00:34:03.370 --> 00:34:08.260 align:middle line:84%
f of x, remember, is the
sum over all the lines

00:34:08.260 --> 00:34:10.510 align:middle line:90%
in our set of lines of L of x.

00:34:10.510 --> 00:34:12.620 align:middle line:84%
So we can break it
up this way also.

00:34:12.620 --> 00:34:15.739 align:middle line:84%
When we add up the constant
parts, we just see what we get.

00:34:15.739 --> 00:34:18.370 align:middle line:84%
We get the number of
lines divided by q.

00:34:18.370 --> 00:34:21.650 align:middle line:84%
And then we have to add up
all the high frequency parts.

00:34:21.650 --> 00:34:28.900 align:middle line:84%
So plus the sum L in our
set of lines of Lh of x.

00:34:28.900 --> 00:34:32.830 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is the
high frequency part of f.

00:34:32.830 --> 00:34:34.845 align:middle line:90%
I'll call it f sub h of x.

00:34:34.845 --> 00:34:36.720 align:middle line:84%
For now you can think
of that as just a name.

00:34:36.720 --> 00:34:40.974 align:middle line:90%


00:34:40.974 --> 00:34:44.350 align:middle line:84%
So this part we
understand quite well.

00:34:44.350 --> 00:34:46.070 align:middle line:90%
We know exactly what it is.

00:34:46.070 --> 00:34:48.190 align:middle line:84%
And so understanding
this function

00:34:48.190 --> 00:34:50.860 align:middle line:84%
boils down to
understanding this part.

00:34:50.860 --> 00:34:54.860 align:middle line:84%
And for understanding this part,
we can use this orthogonality.

00:34:54.860 --> 00:34:56.320 align:middle line:84%
We've written it
as a sum of pieces

00:34:56.320 --> 00:34:57.945 align:middle line:84%
that are each pretty
simple and they're

00:34:57.945 --> 00:34:59.210 align:middle line:90%
orthogonal to each other.

00:34:59.210 --> 00:35:03.280 align:middle line:84%
And so that lets us figure
out or estimate quite well

00:35:03.280 --> 00:35:06.430 align:middle line:90%
the L2 norm of this fh.

00:35:06.430 --> 00:35:10.760 align:middle line:84%
So after the key lemma, I
guess there's the L2 estimate.

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:13.720 align:middle line:90%


00:35:13.720 --> 00:35:26.290 align:middle line:84%
It says this sum x in fq
squared of fh of x squared,

00:35:26.290 --> 00:35:34.330 align:middle line:84%
that's the sum L1 L2 in
L of the sum x and Fq

00:35:34.330 --> 00:35:40.095 align:middle line:90%
squared L1h of x L2 h of x.

00:35:40.095 --> 00:35:52.354 align:middle line:90%


00:35:52.354 --> 00:35:55.760 align:middle line:84%
And because of my
orthogonality in the key lemma,

00:35:55.760 --> 00:35:59.260 align:middle line:84%
almost all of these terms
are less than or equal to 0.

00:35:59.260 --> 00:36:01.940 align:middle line:84%
Namely, if L1 is
different from L2,

00:36:01.940 --> 00:36:05.060 align:middle line:84%
then this sum is less
than or equal to 0.

00:36:05.060 --> 00:36:07.083 align:middle line:84%
So then I'll just
keep the terms where

00:36:07.083 --> 00:36:08.250 align:middle line:90%
they're equal to each other.

00:36:08.250 --> 00:36:24.958 align:middle line:90%


00:36:24.958 --> 00:36:30.140 align:middle line:84%
Now this sum here is
easy to do because I just

00:36:30.140 --> 00:36:32.450 align:middle line:84%
have to think one
line at a time,

00:36:32.450 --> 00:36:35.100 align:middle line:84%
and all the lines will be
equivalent to each other.

00:36:35.100 --> 00:36:38.990 align:middle line:84%
So it's just the number of
lines times whatever this is.

00:36:38.990 --> 00:36:41.870 align:middle line:84%
This thing also is not
very hard to compute,

00:36:41.870 --> 00:36:50.300 align:middle line:84%
but let me say that this is
actually smaller than if I

00:36:50.300 --> 00:36:53.205 align:middle line:90%
did the whole L of x squared.

00:36:53.205 --> 00:36:55.830 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you could just compute
it and write down what happened.

00:36:55.830 --> 00:36:59.270 align:middle line:84%
But anyway if you
take a function

00:36:59.270 --> 00:37:02.600 align:middle line:84%
and you subtract off its
mean, then the L2 norm

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:05.020 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than for
the original function.

00:37:05.020 --> 00:37:06.620 align:middle line:90%
So we could write this.

00:37:06.620 --> 00:37:09.140 align:middle line:84%
And then we can compute
this even in our heads.

00:37:09.140 --> 00:37:13.220 align:middle line:84%
So L of x is 1 at q points,
and otherwise it's 0.

00:37:13.220 --> 00:37:15.160 align:middle line:90%
So this thing here is q.

00:37:15.160 --> 00:37:19.720 align:middle line:84%
So we get the number
of lines times q.

00:37:19.720 --> 00:37:21.620 align:middle line:90%
So that's our L2 estimate.

00:37:21.620 --> 00:38:07.600 align:middle line:90%


00:38:07.600 --> 00:38:11.690 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now let's finish
the proof of theorem two.

00:38:11.690 --> 00:38:13.960 align:middle line:90%
There's theorem two up there.

00:38:13.960 --> 00:38:18.850 align:middle line:84%
We have this hypothesis that
S is a lot smaller than q.

00:38:18.850 --> 00:38:20.500 align:middle line:90%
How does that matter?

00:38:20.500 --> 00:38:24.010 align:middle line:90%
That controls this term.

00:38:24.010 --> 00:38:27.940 align:middle line:84%
So if D was only
as big as L over q,

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:31.850 align:middle line:84%
then this complicated thing
wouldn't come into play.

00:38:31.850 --> 00:38:34.580 align:middle line:84%
And f could be that
big everywhere.

00:38:34.580 --> 00:38:38.560 align:middle line:90%


00:38:38.560 --> 00:38:40.550 align:middle line:90%
So let's see how that works.

00:38:40.550 --> 00:38:43.840 align:middle line:84%
So the number of lines
in my set of lines

00:38:43.840 --> 00:38:48.550 align:middle line:84%
is S times D because I have D
directions and I have S lines

00:38:48.550 --> 00:38:50.110 align:middle line:90%
in each direction.

00:38:50.110 --> 00:39:00.970 align:middle line:84%
So this L over q is
S times D over q.

00:39:00.970 --> 00:39:04.110 align:middle line:84%
And I have a hypothesis
that's S at most q over 2.

00:39:04.110 --> 00:39:06.730 align:middle line:90%


00:39:06.730 --> 00:39:12.490 align:middle line:84%
So that implies that when I
take this ratio, this L over q,

00:39:12.490 --> 00:39:17.980 align:middle line:90%
is less than half of D. Yeah?

00:39:17.980 --> 00:39:21.280 align:middle line:84%
So the quality L
equals S times D,

00:39:21.280 --> 00:39:28.280 align:middle line:84%
does that assume that every
set of lines has the same--

00:39:28.280 --> 00:39:29.540 align:middle line:90%
every L is the same size?

00:39:29.540 --> 00:39:32.140 align:middle line:84%
Because I thought that they
could be different sizes.

00:39:32.140 --> 00:39:33.690 align:middle line:90%
Yes, right.

00:39:33.690 --> 00:39:34.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:34.190 --> 00:39:35.790 align:middle line:90%
That's a good technical catch.

00:39:35.790 --> 00:39:40.030 align:middle line:90%


00:39:40.030 --> 00:39:45.580 align:middle line:84%
So in each direction I
have at most S lines.

00:39:45.580 --> 00:39:49.400 align:middle line:84%
But it might be OK
to work with that.

00:39:49.400 --> 00:39:51.920 align:middle line:84%
But I find it slightly
confusing to keep track of.

00:39:51.920 --> 00:39:54.770 align:middle line:84%
And you can always
add some extra lines.

00:39:54.770 --> 00:40:02.910 align:middle line:84%
And the lines will
still cover the set X.

00:40:02.910 --> 00:40:07.320 align:middle line:84%
So I don't know that this is
crucial, but what I like to do

00:40:07.320 --> 00:40:10.350 align:middle line:84%
is to say that there are equal
to S lines and they cover X,

00:40:10.350 --> 00:40:16.080 align:middle line:84%
and we can say that, and then
it makes this computation clean.

00:40:16.080 --> 00:40:16.580 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:16.580 --> 00:40:19.260 align:middle line:90%


00:40:19.260 --> 00:40:21.690 align:middle line:84%
So this L over q
is less than half

00:40:21.690 --> 00:40:29.460 align:middle line:84%
of D. Now remember that at
each point in X, f of x is D.

00:40:29.460 --> 00:40:33.960 align:middle line:84%
And f of x breaks up as L over
q plus the high frequency part.

00:40:33.960 --> 00:40:38.100 align:middle line:84%
And what we just saw is that L
over q is less than half of D.

00:40:38.100 --> 00:40:41.610 align:middle line:84%
So the high frequency
part is the majority

00:40:41.610 --> 00:40:43.175 align:middle line:90%
of f at those points.

00:40:43.175 --> 00:40:46.440 align:middle line:90%


00:40:46.440 --> 00:40:52.380 align:middle line:84%
So we conclude that
for every x in X,

00:40:52.380 --> 00:40:55.620 align:middle line:84%
the high frequency part
of X is at least half

00:40:55.620 --> 00:41:01.890 align:middle line:84%
of D. I'll just
write greater than D.

00:41:01.890 --> 00:41:07.205 align:middle line:84%
And now we can compare this
with our L2 bound there.

00:41:07.205 --> 00:41:12.342 align:middle line:90%


00:41:12.342 --> 00:41:20.550 align:middle line:84%
So we can say that sum
over all the points

00:41:20.550 --> 00:41:26.010 align:middle line:84%
of f h of x squared, well,
that should be at least as

00:41:26.010 --> 00:41:30.550 align:middle line:84%
big as the points in X times the
number of directions squared.

00:41:30.550 --> 00:41:33.760 align:middle line:84%
So in this sum, some of
these points are in my set x.

00:41:33.760 --> 00:41:36.520 align:middle line:84%
And each of those points,
this has size around D.

00:41:36.520 --> 00:41:38.760 align:middle line:90%
So that contributes this much.

00:41:38.760 --> 00:41:40.740 align:middle line:84%
Plus there are other
points which I really

00:41:40.740 --> 00:41:43.725 align:middle line:90%
don't know what they're doing.

00:41:43.725 --> 00:41:46.320 align:middle line:84%
And then we have the upper
bound the L2 estimate

00:41:46.320 --> 00:41:47.950 align:middle line:90%
that we just proved over there.

00:41:47.950 --> 00:41:52.770 align:middle line:84%
That is upper bounded by
the number of lines times

00:41:52.770 --> 00:41:56.890 align:middle line:90%
q, which is S times D times q.

00:41:56.890 --> 00:42:00.840 align:middle line:90%


00:42:00.840 --> 00:42:02.550 align:middle line:84%
And now we just
rearrange this and it

00:42:02.550 --> 00:42:08.100 align:middle line:84%
will give us some information
about S And D And X and q.

00:42:08.100 --> 00:42:12.250 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to get
the D by itself.

00:42:12.250 --> 00:42:16.050 align:middle line:84%
So I divide by that
and I divide by that.

00:42:16.050 --> 00:42:21.270 align:middle line:84%
And I'm left with D is
bounded by S times q over x.

00:42:21.270 --> 00:42:22.115 align:middle line:90%
There it is.

00:42:22.115 --> 00:42:35.250 align:middle line:90%


00:42:35.250 --> 00:42:36.330 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:42:36.330 --> 00:42:38.670 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I just am
going back and forth

00:42:38.670 --> 00:42:39.930 align:middle line:90%
between that [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:39.930 --> 00:42:41.640 align:middle line:84%
The mean value
here is taken over

00:42:41.640 --> 00:42:45.900 align:middle line:84%
like we're talking about
the mean over the points x?

00:42:45.900 --> 00:42:48.630 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah,
when I say the word

00:42:48.630 --> 00:42:50.820 align:middle line:84%
mean, so the question
was when we said

00:42:50.820 --> 00:42:52.430 align:middle line:90%
mean value the mean over what.

00:42:52.430 --> 00:42:56.820 align:middle line:90%


00:42:56.820 --> 00:42:59.220 align:middle line:90%
So let me put that up here.

00:42:59.220 --> 00:43:06.120 align:middle line:84%
So if I have a function
g Fq squared to C, then

00:43:06.120 --> 00:43:11.370 align:middle line:84%
when I say the mean
value of g, what

00:43:11.370 --> 00:43:19.590 align:middle line:84%
I mean is 1 over q squared
sum x in Fq squared of g of x.

00:43:19.590 --> 00:43:22.235 align:middle line:84%
So it's the mean over
the whole vector space.

00:43:22.235 --> 00:43:30.420 align:middle line:90%


00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:34.170 align:middle line:84%
Other questions or
comments about the proof?

00:43:34.170 --> 00:43:34.670 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:34.670 --> 00:43:37.440 align:middle line:90%


00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:40.710 align:middle line:84%
I am also working on
digesting the proof.

00:43:40.710 --> 00:43:42.540 align:middle line:84%
So the proof is all
about breaking up

00:43:42.540 --> 00:43:46.860 align:middle line:84%
f as this constant part plus
this high frequency part.

00:43:46.860 --> 00:43:50.190 align:middle line:84%
And the proof is saying
that in a certain sense

00:43:50.190 --> 00:43:52.680 align:middle line:84%
the high frequency
part is actually small

00:43:52.680 --> 00:43:54.930 align:middle line:90%
compared to the constant part.

00:43:54.930 --> 00:43:57.540 align:middle line:84%
So I wanted to draw
that out because I

00:43:57.540 --> 00:44:00.455 align:middle line:84%
feel like it helps my intuition
about what the proof is saying.

00:44:00.455 --> 00:44:05.430 align:middle line:90%


00:44:05.430 --> 00:44:09.730 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at
this L2 estimate.

00:44:09.730 --> 00:44:12.720 align:middle line:90%


00:44:12.720 --> 00:44:19.830 align:middle line:84%
Our L2 estimate was
that the sum of h

00:44:19.830 --> 00:44:24.450 align:middle line:84%
of x squared x in
the whole plane

00:44:24.450 --> 00:44:28.880 align:middle line:84%
was bounded by the
number of lines times q.

00:44:28.880 --> 00:44:33.030 align:middle line:90%


00:44:33.030 --> 00:44:35.110 align:middle line:84%
So I want to think
about what this means.

00:44:35.110 --> 00:44:38.500 align:middle line:84%
And it helps me a little bit to
replace the sum by an average.

00:44:38.500 --> 00:44:41.730 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to divide
both sides by q squared.

00:44:41.730 --> 00:44:46.800 align:middle line:84%
So if I take 1 over q
squared, sum x and Fq

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:51.060 align:middle line:84%
squared of h of x
squared, then that's

00:44:51.060 --> 00:44:53.830 align:middle line:84%
bounded by the number
of lines divided by q.

00:44:53.830 --> 00:44:56.430 align:middle line:90%


00:44:56.430 --> 00:44:59.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is an L2
version of an average.

00:44:59.590 --> 00:45:03.930 align:middle line:84%
And by Cauchy-Schwarz,
that controls--

00:45:03.930 --> 00:45:06.600 align:middle line:90%
let's see.

00:45:06.600 --> 00:45:10.440 align:middle line:84%
So if I took a square
root to get an L2 norm,

00:45:10.440 --> 00:45:12.250 align:middle line:84%
I would have a square
root over here.

00:45:12.250 --> 00:45:21.185 align:middle line:84%
And by Cauchy-Schwarz, I would
get the L1 average has a bound.

00:45:21.185 --> 00:45:24.000 align:middle line:90%


00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:29.140 align:middle line:84%
And the bound is now the square
root of number of lines over q.

00:45:29.140 --> 00:45:32.763 align:middle line:90%


00:45:32.763 --> 00:45:34.180 align:middle line:84%
Does that look
right to everybody?

00:45:34.180 --> 00:45:37.650 align:middle line:90%


00:45:37.650 --> 00:45:40.860 align:middle line:84%
So a bit informally,
there might be some points

00:45:40.860 --> 00:45:41.770 align:middle line:90%
x that are different.

00:45:41.770 --> 00:45:44.070 align:middle line:84%
But on average for
a typical point x,

00:45:44.070 --> 00:45:46.980 align:middle line:84%
the high frequency part only
has the size square root

00:45:46.980 --> 00:45:49.680 align:middle line:90%
of L over q.

00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:52.620 align:middle line:84%
Whereas the low frequency
part, the constant part

00:45:52.620 --> 00:45:57.420 align:middle line:84%
has size L over
q at every point.

00:45:57.420 --> 00:46:04.560 align:middle line:84%
Here let's call this constant
part f0, that 0 frequency part.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:08.100 align:middle line:84%
So for comparison,
the size of f0

00:46:08.100 --> 00:46:12.630 align:middle line:84%
of x is always number
of lines over q.

00:46:12.630 --> 00:46:17.850 align:middle line:84%
So the conclusion is that
if the number of lines

00:46:17.850 --> 00:46:25.290 align:middle line:84%
is much bigger than q, then
this is way bigger than that.

00:46:25.290 --> 00:46:30.750 align:middle line:84%
So then the high
frequency part is

00:46:30.750 --> 00:46:35.200 align:middle line:84%
much smaller than the
constant part, on average.

00:46:35.200 --> 00:46:43.740 align:middle line:90%


00:46:43.740 --> 00:46:47.745 align:middle line:84%
So it's telling us that whenever
I add up a lot of lines,

00:46:47.745 --> 00:46:51.510 align:middle line:84%
it has to be significantly
more than a q lines,

00:46:51.510 --> 00:46:56.580 align:middle line:84%
then that sum is pretty close
to being a constant function.

00:46:56.580 --> 00:47:00.150 align:middle line:84%
At a typical point, the
difference from being constant

00:47:00.150 --> 00:47:02.077 align:middle line:84%
is extremely small,
and there may

00:47:02.077 --> 00:47:04.410 align:middle line:84%
be a few points where the
difference from being constant

00:47:04.410 --> 00:47:06.950 align:middle line:84%
is bigger, but there's a
pretty strong bound on that.

00:47:06.950 --> 00:47:24.270 align:middle line:90%


00:47:24.270 --> 00:47:27.905 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
about this orthogonality proof?

00:47:27.905 --> 00:47:35.130 align:middle line:90%


00:47:35.130 --> 00:47:36.120 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:38.880 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Could you go over
again where the inequality h

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:42.600 align:middle line:90%
of x is greater than 1/2 D?

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:46.980 align:middle line:84%
So how do you get that
from the previous slide?

00:47:46.980 --> 00:47:47.890 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:47:47.890 --> 00:47:51.870 align:middle line:84%
So to recap a little
bit, we have these lines

00:47:51.870 --> 00:47:52.960 align:middle line:90%
going in each direction.

00:47:52.960 --> 00:47:54.213 align:middle line:90%
And we have D directions.

00:47:54.213 --> 00:47:56.130 align:middle line:84%
And we add up all the
characteristic functions

00:47:56.130 --> 00:47:57.450 align:middle line:90%
of the lines.

00:47:57.450 --> 00:47:59.130 align:middle line:90%
So that's called f.

00:47:59.130 --> 00:48:02.860 align:middle line:84%
And each point of x is in all
is in a line in every direction.

00:48:02.860 --> 00:48:08.350 align:middle line:84%
So f of x is D. Now we
broke up f into two pieces--

00:48:08.350 --> 00:48:11.350 align:middle line:84%
the constant piece, which
was number of lines over q,

00:48:11.350 --> 00:48:16.230 align:middle line:84%
and then the mean 0 piece
or high frequency piece.

00:48:16.230 --> 00:48:19.450 align:middle line:84%
And I claim that the
constant piece is small.

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:21.228 align:middle line:84%
The constant piece is
less than half of D,

00:48:21.228 --> 00:48:23.520 align:middle line:84%
and that would mean that the
high frequency part should

00:48:23.520 --> 00:48:27.100 align:middle line:84%
be more than half of D. And why
is the constant piece small?

00:48:27.100 --> 00:48:32.820 align:middle line:84%
Well, this L is the number
of directions times S.

00:48:32.820 --> 00:48:34.900 align:middle line:90%
And we plugged it in.

00:48:34.900 --> 00:48:37.540 align:middle line:84%
And we used the fact,
that's S at most q over 2.

00:48:37.540 --> 00:48:39.090 align:middle line:90%
It's one of our hypotheses.

00:48:39.090 --> 00:48:40.300 align:middle line:90%
That's where it fell out.

00:48:40.300 --> 00:48:48.780 align:middle line:90%


00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:49.390 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:49.390 --> 00:48:53.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, I called this early
on the Fourier method.

00:48:53.410 --> 00:48:56.938 align:middle line:84%
We didn't actually mention the
Fourier transform or Fourier

00:48:56.938 --> 00:48:57.730 align:middle line:90%
series of anything.

00:48:57.730 --> 00:48:59.310 align:middle line:90%
We didn't have to.

00:48:59.310 --> 00:49:02.410 align:middle line:84%
We did use
orthogonality crucially,

00:49:02.410 --> 00:49:06.150 align:middle line:84%
which is an idea that I first
saw in Fourier analysis.

00:49:06.150 --> 00:49:08.250 align:middle line:84%
But it is possible
to rewrite this proof

00:49:08.250 --> 00:49:10.950 align:middle line:90%
using the Fourier transform.

00:49:10.950 --> 00:49:16.860 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's worth
doing even though we didn't

00:49:16.860 --> 00:49:18.000 align:middle line:90%
need the Fourier transform.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.790 align:middle line:84%
For this, as we keep going and
do more sophisticated things

00:49:20.790 --> 00:49:25.900 align:middle line:84%
in this spirit, it helps to
have the Fourier transform.

00:49:25.900 --> 00:49:26.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:26.400 --> 00:49:31.860 align:middle line:90%


00:49:31.860 --> 00:49:34.830 align:middle line:84%
I guess the other thing is we
didn't prove the key lemma,

00:49:34.830 --> 00:49:36.900 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:49:36.900 --> 00:49:39.820 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to
prove the key lemma.

00:49:39.820 --> 00:49:41.290 align:middle line:90%
And I'll show you two proofs.

00:49:41.290 --> 00:49:43.250 align:middle line:84%
One of them is direct
and the other one

00:49:43.250 --> 00:49:48.212 align:middle line:84%
is based on the
Fourier transform.

00:49:48.212 --> 00:49:50.425 align:middle line:84%
So I think we can
erase this board here.

00:49:50.425 --> 00:49:52.300 align:middle line:84%
We're just going to talk
about the key lemma.

00:49:52.300 --> 00:50:07.538 align:middle line:90%


00:50:07.538 --> 00:50:10.980 align:middle line:84%
So I'll call this the direct
proof of the key lemma,

00:50:10.980 --> 00:50:12.940 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll also
have a Fourier proof.

00:50:12.940 --> 00:50:18.830 align:middle line:90%


00:50:18.830 --> 00:50:21.150 align:middle line:84%
So actually two
cases in the lemma.

00:50:21.150 --> 00:50:26.215 align:middle line:84%
So the main case is that
L1 and L2 are not parallel.

00:50:26.215 --> 00:50:33.515 align:middle line:90%


00:50:33.515 --> 00:50:37.970 align:middle line:84%
And in this case, the high
frequency parts are orthogonal.

00:50:37.970 --> 00:50:46.190 align:middle line:84%
So sum of x L1 h of x L2 h of x,
in this case, it's exactly zero.

00:50:46.190 --> 00:50:50.150 align:middle line:84%
The less than 0 comes
from the parallel case.

00:50:50.150 --> 00:50:53.550 align:middle line:84%
OK, now there's a lot of
symmetry in this problem.

00:50:53.550 --> 00:50:56.040 align:middle line:84%
And so if we have the
two lines that intersect,

00:50:56.040 --> 00:50:58.663 align:middle line:84%
we can make a linear change
of variables in a translation.

00:50:58.663 --> 00:51:00.830 align:middle line:84%
So that one of them is the
x1 axis and the other one

00:51:00.830 --> 00:51:03.260 align:middle line:90%
is the x2 axis.

00:51:03.260 --> 00:51:08.960 align:middle line:84%
So after change of
variables, L1 is actually

00:51:08.960 --> 00:51:14.130 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to say L1 is the x2
axis and L2 is the x1 axis.

00:51:14.130 --> 00:51:17.510 align:middle line:84%
I know that looks a little
silly, but somewhere there's

00:51:17.510 --> 00:51:18.290 align:middle line:90%
going to be a--

00:51:18.290 --> 00:51:21.590 align:middle line:90%
it's not important.

00:51:21.590 --> 00:51:25.315 align:middle line:84%
So over here is L2
and over here is L1.

00:51:25.315 --> 00:51:28.850 align:middle line:90%


00:51:28.850 --> 00:51:29.760 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:51:29.760 --> 00:51:39.590 align:middle line:84%
Now when we do that, if I take
L1 high of a point x1, x2,

00:51:39.590 --> 00:51:40.873 align:middle line:90%
it only depends.

00:51:40.873 --> 00:51:44.460 align:middle line:90%


00:51:44.460 --> 00:51:48.750 align:middle line:84%
So the function L1 of
x only depends upon x1.

00:51:48.750 --> 00:51:50.940 align:middle line:90%
If x1 is 0, L1 is 1.

00:51:50.940 --> 00:51:53.240 align:middle line:90%
If x1 is not 0, we get 0.

00:51:53.240 --> 00:51:55.710 align:middle line:84%
Then we're subtracting a
constant function from that.

00:51:55.710 --> 00:51:59.120 align:middle line:90%
So it still only depends on x1.

00:51:59.120 --> 00:52:05.160 align:middle line:84%
So this is a function
g of x1 and its mean 0,

00:52:05.160 --> 00:52:10.225 align:middle line:84%
so the sum over x1 and
Fq of g of x1 is 0.

00:52:10.225 --> 00:52:14.390 align:middle line:90%


00:52:14.390 --> 00:52:21.530 align:middle line:84%
Similarly, L2 high of x1,
x2 only depends upon x2

00:52:21.530 --> 00:52:22.885 align:middle line:90%
and it's g of x2.

00:52:22.885 --> 00:52:28.940 align:middle line:90%


00:52:28.940 --> 00:52:30.270 align:middle line:90%
This is the trickiest bit.

00:52:30.270 --> 00:52:32.570 align:middle line:90%
Let me make sure that looks OK.

00:52:32.570 --> 00:52:38.300 align:middle line:84%
So remember L1 is 1 if x0
is 0, and it's 0 otherwise.

00:52:38.300 --> 00:52:39.315 align:middle line:90%
And then we subtract.

00:52:39.315 --> 00:52:41.190 align:middle line:84%
So that's a function
that only depends on x1.

00:52:41.190 --> 00:52:42.360 align:middle line:90%
We subtract off its mean.

00:52:42.360 --> 00:52:44.680 align:middle line:84%
We get a new function
that only depends on x1.

00:52:44.680 --> 00:52:47.540 align:middle line:90%


00:52:47.540 --> 00:52:51.290 align:middle line:84%
I guess it's 1 minus
1 over q if x1 is 0.

00:52:51.290 --> 00:52:54.210 align:middle line:84%
And it's minus 1 over
q if x1 is not 0.

00:52:54.210 --> 00:52:54.925 align:middle line:90%
That's what g is.

00:52:54.925 --> 00:52:59.070 align:middle line:90%


00:52:59.070 --> 00:53:11.270 align:middle line:84%
So now when we sum L1 h
of x1, x2, L2 h of x1, x2.

00:53:11.270 --> 00:53:17.870 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's the sum over
x1, x2 of g of x1, g of x2.

00:53:17.870 --> 00:53:21.080 align:middle line:84%
And now we can just
break up this sum.

00:53:21.080 --> 00:53:25.100 align:middle line:84%
So it's the sum
on x1, of g of x1,

00:53:25.100 --> 00:53:30.185 align:middle line:90%
times the sum on x2 of g of x2.

00:53:30.185 --> 00:53:31.250 align:middle line:90%
It's 0 times 0.

00:53:31.250 --> 00:53:50.970 align:middle line:90%


00:53:50.970 --> 00:53:52.315 align:middle line:90%
Does that look OK to people?

00:53:52.315 --> 00:53:58.550 align:middle line:90%


00:53:58.550 --> 00:54:01.205 align:middle line:84%
OK, then there's the minor
case that they're parallel.

00:54:01.205 --> 00:54:10.100 align:middle line:90%


00:54:10.100 --> 00:54:12.140 align:middle line:84%
I don't have anything
super instructive to say

00:54:12.140 --> 00:54:13.080 align:middle line:90%
about this case.

00:54:13.080 --> 00:54:17.150 align:middle line:84%
They might as well both be
parallel to the x2 axis.

00:54:17.150 --> 00:54:19.020 align:middle line:84%
It's not hard to
compute it by hand,

00:54:19.020 --> 00:54:22.220 align:middle line:84%
and you'll see
that it's negative.

00:54:22.220 --> 00:54:24.440 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to not
do it on the board

00:54:24.440 --> 00:54:26.340 align:middle line:84%
because I think it's
not very illuminating.

00:54:26.340 --> 00:54:31.490 align:middle line:90%


00:54:31.490 --> 00:54:34.970 align:middle line:84%
So that's one way to
prove the key lemma.

00:54:34.970 --> 00:54:38.960 align:middle line:84%
But the whole setup also
has a nice relationship

00:54:38.960 --> 00:54:40.140 align:middle line:90%
to Fourier analysis.

00:54:40.140 --> 00:54:44.040 align:middle line:84%
And we can also use Fourier
analysis to prove the key lemma.

00:54:44.040 --> 00:54:46.610 align:middle line:84%
And if we do it that
way, we can justify

00:54:46.610 --> 00:54:50.270 align:middle line:84%
in a precise way saying that
something is the zero frequency

00:54:50.270 --> 00:54:51.730 align:middle line:90%
part or the high frequency part.

00:54:51.730 --> 00:54:55.155 align:middle line:90%


00:54:55.155 --> 00:54:55.655 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:55.655 --> 00:55:21.300 align:middle line:90%


00:55:21.300 --> 00:55:24.470 align:middle line:84%
So let me remind everybody
how Fourier analysis works

00:55:24.470 --> 00:55:25.780 align:middle line:90%
over finite fields.

00:55:25.780 --> 00:55:45.386 align:middle line:90%


00:55:45.386 --> 00:55:52.220 align:middle line:84%
So I have a Fourier
analysis based

00:55:52.220 --> 00:55:55.790 align:middle line:84%
on having some group
homomorphism from your group

00:55:55.790 --> 00:55:57.090 align:middle line:90%
into C star.

00:55:57.090 --> 00:56:03.020 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to call it E. So
E is a map from Fq to C star.

00:56:03.020 --> 00:56:04.740 align:middle line:90%
Think of it as Fq with addition.

00:56:04.740 --> 00:56:06.870 align:middle line:84%
So this is a group,
an abelian group.

00:56:06.870 --> 00:56:09.420 align:middle line:84%
That's an abelian group, complex
numbers with multiplication.

00:56:09.420 --> 00:56:11.696 align:middle line:90%
This is a homomorphism.

00:56:11.696 --> 00:56:15.530 align:middle line:90%


00:56:15.530 --> 00:56:22.590 align:middle line:84%
And I want it to be non-trivial,
to not just send everything to 1

00:56:22.590 --> 00:56:28.050 align:middle line:84%
So for example, if
q equals p is prime,

00:56:28.050 --> 00:56:33.540 align:middle line:84%
then it would be e of x is
e to the 2 PI i x over p.

00:56:33.540 --> 00:56:37.280 align:middle line:90%


00:56:37.280 --> 00:56:39.560 align:middle line:84%
And if q is not prime, it
takes a little bit more

00:56:39.560 --> 00:56:41.700 align:middle line:84%
doing to write down
a homomorphism.

00:56:41.700 --> 00:56:43.240 align:middle line:84%
But there is one
that's not true.

00:56:43.240 --> 00:56:47.618 align:middle line:90%


00:56:47.618 --> 00:56:50.000 align:middle line:84%
So now suppose I
have a function on Fq

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:54.980 align:middle line:84%
to the D. It has a
Fourier transform.

00:56:54.980 --> 00:56:59.510 align:middle line:84%
So the Fourier transform
of C is defined

00:56:59.510 --> 00:57:07.430 align:middle line:84%
to be sum over q and Fq to
the d, f of x, e of negative

00:57:07.430 --> 00:57:11.910 align:middle line:90%
x dot C. So there's x.

00:57:11.910 --> 00:57:13.530 align:middle line:90%
C. This is a dot product.

00:57:13.530 --> 00:57:15.690 align:middle line:90%
It's just x1c1 plus, x2c2.

00:57:15.690 --> 00:57:19.580 align:middle line:90%


00:57:19.580 --> 00:57:21.060 align:middle line:90%
So that's the Fourier transform.

00:57:21.060 --> 00:57:25.820 align:middle line:84%
It looks more or less like how
it looks in Euclidean space.

00:57:25.820 --> 00:57:29.690 align:middle line:90%


00:57:29.690 --> 00:57:38.090 align:middle line:90%
So this C also lives in fq.

00:57:38.090 --> 00:57:40.790 align:middle line:84%
There are two main really
fundamental theorems

00:57:40.790 --> 00:57:42.960 align:middle line:90%
about Fourier transform.

00:57:42.960 --> 00:57:45.770 align:middle line:84%
One of them is Fourier
inversion and the other one

00:57:45.770 --> 00:57:48.170 align:middle line:84%
is Plancherel theorem
with orthogonality.

00:57:48.170 --> 00:57:50.210 align:middle line:84%
And in the finite
field setting, they

00:57:50.210 --> 00:57:51.690 align:middle line:90%
work out in the following way.

00:57:51.690 --> 00:57:56.240 align:middle line:84%
So theorem one,
Fourier inversion f

00:57:56.240 --> 00:58:00.830 align:middle line:84%
of x is the sum
xi in Fq to the d.

00:58:00.830 --> 00:58:04.430 align:middle line:84%
And here we need
to take an average.

00:58:04.430 --> 00:58:09.740 align:middle line:90%
f hat of xi e of x dot xi.

00:58:09.740 --> 00:58:13.160 align:middle line:84%
So it looks like Fourier
inversion in Euclidean space,

00:58:13.160 --> 00:58:15.770 align:middle line:84%
although there's
this average here.

00:58:15.770 --> 00:58:17.510 align:middle line:84%
Maybe worth saying
that there are

00:58:17.510 --> 00:58:21.030 align:middle line:84%
several reasonable conventions
that you might put about it.

00:58:21.030 --> 00:58:23.540 align:middle line:84%
Somewhere in this setup,
we need to divide something

00:58:23.540 --> 00:58:25.995 align:middle line:84%
by some powers of
q And there are

00:58:25.995 --> 00:58:27.620 align:middle line:84%
several reasonable
conventions, and you

00:58:27.620 --> 00:58:30.590 align:middle line:84%
see different conventions
in different places.

00:58:30.590 --> 00:58:32.960 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, this is
the one that I picked.

00:58:32.960 --> 00:58:34.920 align:middle line:90%
And I never remember it.

00:58:34.920 --> 00:58:36.860 align:middle line:84%
So I always take the
function 1 and compute

00:58:36.860 --> 00:58:39.038 align:middle line:84%
its Fourier transform and
check that this works.

00:58:39.038 --> 00:58:40.830 align:middle line:84%
And that tells me I
have this factor right.

00:58:40.830 --> 00:58:43.990 align:middle line:90%


00:58:43.990 --> 00:58:47.316 align:middle line:90%
And theorem two is Plancherel.

00:58:47.316 --> 00:58:51.740 align:middle line:90%


00:58:51.740 --> 00:58:56.180 align:middle line:84%
So that says that if
I take the sum over Fq

00:58:56.180 --> 00:59:01.520 align:middle line:84%
to the d of f of x, g
of x bar, then that's

00:59:01.520 --> 00:59:03.660 align:middle line:84%
equivalent to a sum
on the Fourier side.

00:59:03.660 --> 00:59:05.250 align:middle line:84%
And there's also
a normalization.

00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:14.726 align:middle line:84%
So that's 1 over q to the d sum
x and sum xi and Fq to the d,

00:59:14.726 --> 00:59:20.330 align:middle line:90%
f hat of xi g hat of xi bar.

00:59:20.330 --> 00:59:23.220 align:middle line:84%
So again, if you compute
a simple example,

00:59:23.220 --> 00:59:25.620 align:middle line:84%
you'll see that this is
the right normalization.

00:59:25.620 --> 00:59:36.670 align:middle line:90%


00:59:36.670 --> 00:59:41.140 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now if you take the
characteristic function

00:59:41.140 --> 00:59:44.060 align:middle line:84%
of the line, you can take
its Fourier transform.

00:59:44.060 --> 00:59:45.640 align:middle line:84%
And something
interesting happens

00:59:45.640 --> 00:59:51.280 align:middle line:84%
that represents an important
connection between lines

00:59:51.280 --> 00:59:53.380 align:middle line:84%
in the Fourier
transform and therefore

00:59:53.380 --> 00:59:56.950 align:middle line:84%
between projection theory
and the Fourier transform.

00:59:56.950 --> 00:59:58.130 align:middle line:90%
So here is what happens.

00:59:58.130 --> 01:00:07.300 align:middle line:84%
So suppose L is an affine
line in Fq squared,

01:00:07.300 --> 01:00:14.150 align:middle line:84%
or really the characteristic
function of the affine line

01:00:14.150 --> 01:00:19.480 align:middle line:84%
So then it has a perp, so
L perp is the set of xi

01:00:19.480 --> 01:00:29.950 align:middle line:84%
so that xi dot x1 minus x2 is 0
for any x1 and x2 in the line L.

01:00:29.950 --> 01:00:32.160 align:middle line:84%
So in Euclidean space
this would look like this.

01:00:32.160 --> 01:00:34.711 align:middle line:90%


01:00:34.711 --> 01:00:40.330 align:middle line:84%
To here is my line
L. This is x space.

01:00:40.330 --> 01:00:47.740 align:middle line:84%
And then over here in xi
space I would have L perp.

01:00:47.740 --> 01:00:49.860 align:middle line:84%
Notice that L perp
always goes through 0.

01:00:49.860 --> 01:00:52.450 align:middle line:90%


01:00:52.450 --> 01:00:58.510 align:middle line:90%
So here is my x1 and x2.

01:00:58.510 --> 01:01:01.670 align:middle line:84%
So this direction here is
a tangent direction to L.

01:01:01.670 --> 01:01:06.160 align:middle line:84%
And then these are the
perpendicular directions.

01:01:06.160 --> 01:01:07.330 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:01:07.330 --> 01:01:14.260 align:middle line:84%
So proposition, if
you take L hat of xi,

01:01:14.260 --> 01:01:16.360 align:middle line:90%
we take its absolute value.

01:01:16.360 --> 01:01:18.160 align:middle line:90%
There are two cases.

01:01:18.160 --> 01:01:25.540 align:middle line:84%
One of them is that you get q
And that's if xi is in L perp.

01:01:25.540 --> 01:01:27.880 align:middle line:90%
And the other one is you get 0.

01:01:27.880 --> 01:01:32.440 align:middle line:84%
And that's if xi
is not in L pip.

01:01:32.440 --> 01:01:34.660 align:middle line:84%
So the Fourier transform
of a line, first of all

01:01:34.660 --> 01:01:36.230 align:middle line:90%
has is very sparse.

01:01:36.230 --> 01:01:38.230 align:middle line:90%
It's 0 almost everywhere.

01:01:38.230 --> 01:01:41.415 align:middle line:84%
The only places where it's not 0
are on this perpendicular line.

01:01:41.415 --> 01:01:48.624 align:middle line:90%


01:01:48.624 --> 01:01:51.700 align:middle line:84%
So I think it is
a good experience

01:01:51.700 --> 01:01:55.210 align:middle line:84%
to compute this out and
check that it happens.

01:01:55.210 --> 01:02:00.670 align:middle line:84%
When you write down
this sum, this sum

01:02:00.670 --> 01:02:03.140 align:middle line:84%
will reduce to a
geometric series.

01:02:03.140 --> 01:02:04.850 align:middle line:84%
And then you can sum
the geometric series

01:02:04.850 --> 01:02:06.986 align:middle line:84%
and you can see
exactly what happens.

01:02:06.986 --> 01:02:11.775 align:middle line:84%
So this is an exercise
on the homework.

01:02:11.775 --> 01:02:18.460 align:middle line:90%


01:02:18.460 --> 01:02:22.780 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we'll also do this thing
of subtracting off the mean.

01:02:22.780 --> 01:02:25.450 align:middle line:84%
And that has a very
natural interpretation

01:02:25.450 --> 01:02:26.796 align:middle line:90%
in Fourier analysis.

01:02:26.796 --> 01:02:30.850 align:middle line:90%


01:02:30.850 --> 01:02:32.100 align:middle line:90%
Let's erase this.

01:02:32.100 --> 01:02:43.210 align:middle line:90%


01:02:43.210 --> 01:02:49.250 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a function g
from Fq to the d goes to C,

01:02:49.250 --> 01:02:55.270 align:middle line:84%
then we can write g as 1
over q to the d sum over xi g

01:02:55.270 --> 01:02:58.270 align:middle line:90%
hat of xi, E of x dot xi.

01:02:58.270 --> 01:03:01.340 align:middle line:84%
And one of these frequencies
is often very special,

01:03:01.340 --> 01:03:03.050 align:middle line:90%
namely the frequency zero.

01:03:03.050 --> 01:03:05.410 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just going to
break up this sum.

01:03:05.410 --> 01:03:11.230 align:middle line:84%
It's 1 over q to
the d g hat of 0

01:03:11.230 --> 01:03:17.770 align:middle line:84%
plus the sum over the
non-zero xi 1 over q

01:03:17.770 --> 01:03:24.040 align:middle line:90%
to the d g hat xi of x dot xi.

01:03:24.040 --> 01:03:25.420 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:03:25.420 --> 01:03:28.420 align:middle line:84%
So if you think about
what this is, g hat of 0

01:03:28.420 --> 01:03:32.140 align:middle line:84%
is just the sum of the values
of g, and then I divide by that.

01:03:32.140 --> 01:03:33.890 align:middle line:90%
I get this formula here.

01:03:33.890 --> 01:03:37.750 align:middle line:90%
That's the mean value of g.

01:03:37.750 --> 01:03:44.320 align:middle line:84%
So this is g0 and it's
the mean value of g.

01:03:44.320 --> 01:03:48.702 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here
we'll call g high.

01:03:48.702 --> 01:03:51.410 align:middle line:84%
g high is g minus
its mean value.

01:03:51.410 --> 01:03:52.410 align:middle line:90%
So it has mean 0.

01:03:52.410 --> 01:03:58.150 align:middle line:90%


01:03:58.150 --> 01:04:00.020 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we
did with our lines.

01:04:00.020 --> 01:04:02.210 align:middle line:84%
This is the zero
frequency part of L.

01:04:02.210 --> 01:04:04.490 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
nonzero frequency.

01:04:04.490 --> 01:04:06.620 align:middle line:84%
Or I called it high
frequency part of L.

01:04:06.620 --> 01:04:09.520 align:middle line:84%
So from the Fourier
analysis point

01:04:09.520 --> 01:04:12.570 align:middle line:84%
of view, that's what these
things precisely mean.

01:04:12.570 --> 01:04:17.830 align:middle line:90%


01:04:17.830 --> 01:04:24.550 align:middle line:84%
Now we can put this together
to give a new explanation

01:04:24.550 --> 01:04:26.895 align:middle line:90%
of the key orthogonality lemma.

01:04:26.895 --> 01:04:30.128 align:middle line:90%


01:04:30.128 --> 01:04:31.670 align:middle line:90%
Where should I put it?

01:04:31.670 --> 01:04:36.730 align:middle line:90%


01:04:36.730 --> 01:04:39.910 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so we gave one proof
of the key lemma over here.

01:04:39.910 --> 01:04:41.340 align:middle line:90%
We can do now another one.

01:04:41.340 --> 01:04:51.810 align:middle line:90%


01:04:51.810 --> 01:04:52.310 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:04:52.310 --> 01:04:56.310 align:middle line:84%
So let's give the Fourier
proof of the key lemma.

01:04:56.310 --> 01:04:59.680 align:middle line:90%


01:04:59.680 --> 01:05:05.260 align:middle line:84%
We'll still do the main case,
which is that L1 and L2 are not

01:05:05.260 --> 01:05:06.430 align:middle line:90%
parallel.

01:05:06.430 --> 01:05:09.340 align:middle line:84%
And that's where we get
literal orthogonality.

01:05:09.340 --> 01:05:19.990 align:middle line:84%
Then we get that the sum of
L1 h of x and L2 h of x is 0.

01:05:19.990 --> 01:05:21.290 align:middle line:90%
How will we do it?

01:05:21.290 --> 01:05:23.426 align:middle line:84%
We'll evaluate it
with Plancherel.

01:05:23.426 --> 01:05:47.170 align:middle line:90%


01:05:47.170 --> 01:05:50.020 align:middle line:84%
So that's Plancherel,
theorem two.

01:05:50.020 --> 01:05:53.210 align:middle line:84%
And now I have the
high part here.

01:05:53.210 --> 01:05:54.440 align:middle line:90%
What does the high part mean?

01:05:54.440 --> 01:05:58.240 align:middle line:84%
The high part means I
crossed out the 0 frequency.

01:05:58.240 --> 01:06:05.980 align:middle line:84%
So this is 1 over q squared
times the sum on non-zero xi,

01:06:05.980 --> 01:06:11.200 align:middle line:90%
L1 hat of xi, L2 hat xi.

01:06:11.200 --> 01:06:15.730 align:middle line:84%
So if you compare the Fourier
transform of L1 and L1 high,

01:06:15.730 --> 01:06:18.230 align:middle line:84%
the only difference
is the zero frequency.

01:06:18.230 --> 01:06:21.007 align:middle line:84%
I take the zero frequency
here and I throw it out.

01:06:21.007 --> 01:06:22.340 align:middle line:90%
All the other ones are the same.

01:06:22.340 --> 01:06:25.180 align:middle line:90%
So this is the same as this.

01:06:25.180 --> 01:06:29.500 align:middle line:90%
OK, now I'll make a picture.

01:06:29.500 --> 01:06:41.080 align:middle line:84%
So here in x space I have a
line L1 and I have a line L2.

01:06:41.080 --> 01:06:44.720 align:middle line:84%
What happens in Fourier
space, xi space.

01:06:44.720 --> 01:06:50.820 align:middle line:84%
Well there's a L1 perp
and then there's L2 perp.

01:06:50.820 --> 01:06:54.370 align:middle line:90%


01:06:54.370 --> 01:07:00.340 align:middle line:84%
And L1 and L2 perp
intersect only at 0.

01:07:00.340 --> 01:07:03.136 align:middle line:84%
So here I'm summing over
non-zero frequencies.

01:07:03.136 --> 01:07:06.670 align:middle line:90%


01:07:06.670 --> 01:07:16.800 align:middle line:84%
So if xi is non-zero then
either xi is not in L1 perp

01:07:16.800 --> 01:07:22.900 align:middle line:84%
or xi is not in L2 perp,
because those two perps,

01:07:22.900 --> 01:07:26.410 align:middle line:84%
they only intersect
at the origin.

01:07:26.410 --> 01:07:30.760 align:middle line:84%
But this function is only
supported when xi is in L1 perp,

01:07:30.760 --> 01:07:33.870 align:middle line:84%
and this one is only supported
when xi is in L2 perp.

01:07:33.870 --> 01:07:36.920 align:middle line:84%
So at every xi in this sum,
one of these guys is zero.

01:07:36.920 --> 01:07:43.350 align:middle line:90%


01:07:43.350 --> 01:07:45.540 align:middle line:84%
Or to put it a little
bit differently,

01:07:45.540 --> 01:07:49.770 align:middle line:84%
these two functions have
disjoint Fourier support.

01:07:49.770 --> 01:07:51.130 align:middle line:90%
So they are orthogonal.

01:07:51.130 --> 01:08:10.140 align:middle line:90%


01:08:10.140 --> 01:08:13.562 align:middle line:84%
So these are the two
main classical techniques

01:08:13.562 --> 01:08:15.270 align:middle line:84%
of projection theory,
the double counting

01:08:15.270 --> 01:08:19.170 align:middle line:84%
argument, and the Fourier
orthogonality argument.

01:08:19.170 --> 01:08:24.090 align:middle line:84%
They're each not that
difficult, but it actually

01:08:24.090 --> 01:08:27.145 align:middle line:84%
is really pretty hard
to go beyond them,

01:08:27.145 --> 01:08:28.770 align:middle line:84%
even though there's
a lot of situations

01:08:28.770 --> 01:08:31.050 align:middle line:90%
where they're not sharp.

01:08:31.050 --> 01:08:34.380 align:middle line:84%
So that's a theme
that we'll get to.

01:08:34.380 --> 01:08:38.370 align:middle line:84%
But before we get to that theme,
we'll explore these for a while

01:08:38.370 --> 01:08:40.560 align:middle line:84%
and we'll see that
a bunch of people

01:08:40.560 --> 01:08:43.109 align:middle line:84%
have used them, in fact, in
different areas of math to do

01:08:43.109 --> 01:08:44.790 align:middle line:84%
some different things,
and it's things

01:08:44.790 --> 01:08:46.180 align:middle line:90%
that I think are interesting.

01:08:46.180 --> 01:08:48.720 align:middle line:90%


01:08:48.720 --> 01:08:53.700 align:middle line:84%
So the next thing that we'll
do is the more analytic setting

01:08:53.700 --> 01:08:57.700 align:middle line:84%
of working in R2 instead
of over a finite field,

01:08:57.700 --> 01:09:01.290 align:middle line:84%
and having balls
instead of points.

01:09:01.290 --> 01:09:05.970 align:middle line:84%
And I waved my hands about it
last class about exactly what

01:09:05.970 --> 01:09:08.920 align:middle line:90%
we would try to prove.

01:09:08.920 --> 01:09:12.090 align:middle line:84%
And so in our last
10 minutes, I'll

01:09:12.090 --> 01:09:13.689 align:middle line:90%
introduce the setup with balls.

01:09:13.689 --> 01:09:16.740 align:middle line:84%
And I'll tell you what are
the analog of theorem one

01:09:16.740 --> 01:09:18.880 align:middle line:84%
and theorem two and
this conjecture.

01:09:18.880 --> 01:09:23.189 align:middle line:90%


01:09:23.189 --> 01:09:26.558 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll see the proofs
of all that next class.

01:09:26.558 --> 01:09:29.100 align:middle line:84%
And we'll see the proofs are
morally the same as these proofs

01:09:29.100 --> 01:09:31.290 align:middle line:84%
in finite fields,
but with a little bit

01:09:31.290 --> 01:09:37.120 align:middle line:84%
of extra technical issues from
working in Euclidean space.

01:09:37.120 --> 01:09:37.620 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:37.620 --> 01:09:53.580 align:middle line:90%


01:09:53.580 --> 01:09:54.750 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:09:54.750 --> 01:10:04.115 align:middle line:84%
So let's do a setup with
balls, setup in R2 with balls.

01:10:04.115 --> 01:10:08.580 align:middle line:90%


01:10:08.580 --> 01:10:09.430 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:10:09.430 --> 01:10:16.950 align:middle line:84%
So our set X is going to
be a set of disjoint unit

01:10:16.950 --> 01:10:23.400 align:middle line:90%
balls in a large ball B2R.

01:10:23.400 --> 01:10:26.200 align:middle line:84%
And then D, our
set of directions,

01:10:26.200 --> 01:10:28.830 align:middle line:84%
I'll think of it
as a subset of S1.

01:10:28.830 --> 01:10:34.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is a set of directions
that we'll do projections in.

01:10:34.530 --> 01:10:35.973 align:middle line:90%
And they will also be disjoint.

01:10:35.973 --> 01:10:37.890 align:middle line:84%
And what I'm going to
put here is that they're

01:10:37.890 --> 01:10:41.910 align:middle line:90%
1 over R separated.

01:10:41.910 --> 01:10:45.790 align:middle line:84%
So you can think of
D as a set of angles.

01:10:45.790 --> 01:10:49.210 align:middle line:84%
And any two angles are at least
1 over R apart from each other.

01:10:49.210 --> 01:10:51.820 align:middle line:84%
The reason for that is if they
are closer together than that,

01:10:51.820 --> 01:10:53.310 align:middle line:84%
the two projections
would basically

01:10:53.310 --> 01:10:57.420 align:middle line:84%
be the same in terms of what
they do to a set of unit balls

01:10:57.420 --> 01:11:00.210 align:middle line:90%
in a ball of radius R.

01:11:00.210 --> 01:11:09.510 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's X and D.
And then our S, S of XD

01:11:09.510 --> 01:11:12.120 align:middle line:84%
is the maximum
over any direction

01:11:12.120 --> 01:11:16.350 align:middle line:84%
in our set of directions of
the size of the projection of X

01:11:16.350 --> 01:11:17.590 align:middle line:90%
in that direction.

01:11:17.590 --> 01:11:19.030 align:middle line:84%
So this is a
one-dimensional set.

01:11:19.030 --> 01:11:20.830 align:middle line:84%
It's basically a set
of unit intervals.

01:11:20.830 --> 01:11:23.180 align:middle line:84%
And this absolute
value is its length.

01:11:23.180 --> 01:11:30.600 align:middle line:90%


01:11:30.600 --> 01:11:31.540 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:11:31.540 --> 01:11:35.970 align:middle line:84%
So we could ask just in terms of
the size of X and the size of D,

01:11:35.970 --> 01:11:38.760 align:middle line:84%
what can you say about S
and how does it compare

01:11:38.760 --> 01:11:40.980 align:middle line:90%
to the finite field case?

01:11:40.980 --> 01:11:43.410 align:middle line:84%
And we saw last time
that it's rather

01:11:43.410 --> 01:11:47.520 align:middle line:84%
different from the finite field
case because of an example

01:11:47.520 --> 01:11:51.000 align:middle line:84%
where X is very
clumped together.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:53.850 align:middle line:84%
So let me put up here
a couple of examples

01:11:53.850 --> 01:11:55.565 align:middle line:90%
in our new geometric setup.

01:11:55.565 --> 01:12:03.330 align:middle line:90%


01:12:03.330 --> 01:12:14.840 align:middle line:84%
So example one is a square
grid that's spaced out.

01:12:14.840 --> 01:12:18.030 align:middle line:90%


01:12:18.030 --> 01:12:19.535 align:middle line:90%
OK, so it looks like this.

01:12:19.535 --> 01:12:24.990 align:middle line:90%


01:12:24.990 --> 01:12:28.890 align:middle line:90%
It's going to be an n by n grid.

01:12:28.890 --> 01:12:31.960 align:middle line:90%
And it's inside of an R ball.

01:12:31.960 --> 01:12:34.110 align:middle line:84%
But I'm going to make it
as spread out as possible.

01:12:34.110 --> 01:12:37.950 align:middle line:84%
So the distance here
is about R over N.

01:12:37.950 --> 01:12:43.540 align:middle line:84%
So that's my set X. And D
could be the same as before.

01:12:43.540 --> 01:12:53.280 align:middle line:84%
It could be the directions
with slope a1 over a2,

01:12:53.280 --> 01:13:00.960 align:middle line:84%
where a1 and a2 are integers
going from 1 up to A.

01:13:00.960 --> 01:13:05.110 align:middle line:84%
And if you compute how
big the projection is,

01:13:05.110 --> 01:13:09.792 align:middle line:84%
it's the same as
before, A times N.

01:13:09.792 --> 01:13:11.250 align:middle line:84%
That's the same
thing we got before

01:13:11.250 --> 01:13:14.670 align:middle line:84%
at the beginning of class,
except that the projection is

01:13:14.670 --> 01:13:18.340 align:middle line:84%
never bigger than R. If you
direct a whole ball of radius R,

01:13:18.340 --> 01:13:21.970 align:middle line:84%
you get an interval of length R.
So it's never bigger than that.

01:13:21.970 --> 01:13:24.610 align:middle line:84%
So I'll put the
minimum this thing.

01:13:24.610 --> 01:13:28.545 align:middle line:90%


01:13:28.545 --> 01:13:30.010 align:middle line:90%
So there's one scenario.

01:13:30.010 --> 01:13:32.845 align:middle line:84%
This is an integer grid, which
was an important example before.

01:13:32.845 --> 01:13:35.220 align:middle line:84%
But another thing you can do
is you can take these points

01:13:35.220 --> 01:13:36.387 align:middle line:90%
and clump them way together.

01:13:36.387 --> 01:13:40.320 align:middle line:90%


01:13:40.320 --> 01:13:47.280 align:middle line:90%
So example two is a clump.

01:13:47.280 --> 01:13:51.695 align:middle line:84%
So I take a ball of radius N
And I fill it with unit balls.

01:13:51.695 --> 01:13:57.030 align:middle line:90%


01:13:57.030 --> 01:14:00.010 align:middle line:84%
So we still have the number
of balls is around N squared.

01:14:00.010 --> 01:14:03.210 align:middle line:84%
But they're much more
clumped together.

01:14:03.210 --> 01:14:08.760 align:middle line:84%
And when you do that, pi
theta of X is only around N.

01:14:08.760 --> 01:14:11.080 align:middle line:84%
You project this set
X in any direction,

01:14:11.080 --> 01:14:13.050 align:middle line:84%
it will be an
interval of length N.

01:14:13.050 --> 01:14:16.350 align:middle line:84%
And so that's true
for everything.

01:14:16.350 --> 01:14:17.890 align:middle line:84%
And if you compare
these examples,

01:14:17.890 --> 01:14:29.500 align:middle line:84%
you'll see that this one has
much smaller S's than this one.

01:14:29.500 --> 01:14:33.900 align:middle line:84%
This example is much more
extreme than the grid.

01:14:33.900 --> 01:14:38.860 align:middle line:84%
OK, so it turns out that
just asking the question,

01:14:38.860 --> 01:14:40.650 align:middle line:84%
if you know the
cardinality of X,

01:14:40.650 --> 01:14:45.720 align:middle line:84%
and you know the cardinality
of D, what can you say about S?

01:14:45.720 --> 01:14:47.045 align:middle line:90%
We'll answer that question.

01:14:47.045 --> 01:14:48.670 align:middle line:84%
That's a somewhat
interesting question.

01:14:48.670 --> 01:14:50.340 align:middle line:90%
And we'll answer it.

01:14:50.340 --> 01:14:52.265 align:middle line:84%
But it's not the most
interesting question.

01:14:52.265 --> 01:14:55.795 align:middle line:90%


01:14:55.795 --> 01:14:57.670 align:middle line:84%
There's a phenomenon
that's more interesting,

01:14:57.670 --> 01:14:59.920 align:middle line:84%
which is that as the
points get spread out,

01:14:59.920 --> 01:15:01.346 align:middle line:90%
you get stronger estimates.

01:15:01.346 --> 01:15:04.020 align:middle line:90%


01:15:04.020 --> 01:15:07.110 align:middle line:84%
So what does it mean that
the points get spread out?

01:15:07.110 --> 01:15:10.470 align:middle line:84%
You need to have
some rules about it.

01:15:10.470 --> 01:15:14.190 align:middle line:84%
How do we make that precise
that they're spread out?

01:15:14.190 --> 01:15:16.590 align:middle line:84%
So being clumped
together means there

01:15:16.590 --> 01:15:19.800 align:middle line:84%
are a lot of points
in a small ball.

01:15:19.800 --> 01:15:23.520 align:middle line:84%
And we can quantify that
in the following way.

01:15:23.520 --> 01:15:30.000 align:middle line:84%
N sub x of r is the maximum
over any choice of center

01:15:30.000 --> 01:15:35.150 align:middle line:84%
of the size of X in the ball
around center c with radius r.

01:15:35.150 --> 01:15:38.520 align:middle line:90%


01:15:38.520 --> 01:15:40.860 align:middle line:84%
So you can see that this
quantity would be quite large

01:15:40.860 --> 01:15:45.051 align:middle line:84%
in this example, especially
if you took little r to be N.

01:15:45.051 --> 01:15:47.800 align:middle line:84%
And it would be a lot
smaller in this example.

01:15:47.800 --> 01:15:49.360 align:middle line:84%
So that point is
more spread out.

01:15:49.360 --> 01:15:54.921 align:middle line:90%


01:15:54.921 --> 01:15:59.670 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out it doesn't just
matter how our set of points

01:15:59.670 --> 01:16:00.990 align:middle line:90%
is spaced.

01:16:00.990 --> 01:16:05.000 align:middle line:84%
It also matters how our set
of directions is spaced.

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:07.020 align:middle line:90%
So we'll talk about that also.

01:16:07.020 --> 01:16:15.202 align:middle line:84%
So N sub D of R is
the maximum over any--

01:16:15.202 --> 01:16:16.910 align:middle line:84%
actually let me give
this another letter.

01:16:16.910 --> 01:16:26.120 align:middle line:84%
I'll call it rho, any
arc of length rho in S1.

01:16:26.120 --> 01:16:27.830 align:middle line:84%
So we have the
directions as a subset

01:16:27.830 --> 01:16:35.960 align:middle line:84%
of S1 of the number of
the directions in the arc.

01:16:35.960 --> 01:16:38.180 align:middle line:84%
So if you pick a
particular parameter,

01:16:38.180 --> 01:16:42.080 align:middle line:84%
a size rho, and you ask how
many directions are there

01:16:42.080 --> 01:16:44.570 align:middle line:90%
in an arc of size of rho.

01:16:44.570 --> 01:16:45.660 align:middle line:90%
So that's this thing.

01:16:45.660 --> 01:16:55.575 align:middle line:90%


01:16:55.575 --> 01:16:59.240 align:middle line:84%
So you could describe our
goal in projection theory

01:16:59.240 --> 01:17:01.610 align:middle line:84%
in Euclidean space
in the following way.

01:17:01.610 --> 01:17:04.130 align:middle line:84%
Given some information
about this thing

01:17:04.130 --> 01:17:18.980 align:middle line:84%
and that thing, try to
estimate S And D And X.

01:17:18.980 --> 01:17:21.140 align:middle line:90%
You can phrase it that way.

01:17:21.140 --> 01:17:23.512 align:middle line:84%
And then there's a
whole world of questions

01:17:23.512 --> 01:17:25.220 align:middle line:84%
because there's a lot
of different things

01:17:25.220 --> 01:17:29.030 align:middle line:84%
you could assume
about N, X, and D.

01:17:29.030 --> 01:17:31.580 align:middle line:84%
There is one
particular scenario,

01:17:31.580 --> 01:17:33.320 align:middle line:84%
one particular set
of assumptions that

01:17:33.320 --> 01:17:34.770 align:middle line:90%
has been investigated a lot.

01:17:34.770 --> 01:17:37.350 align:middle line:84%
And it's not the
only interesting one,

01:17:37.350 --> 01:17:43.430 align:middle line:84%
but it seems to be important
and a good thing to focus on.

01:17:43.430 --> 01:17:56.960 align:middle line:84%
So you could say that x is an
alpha dimensional set of balls

01:17:56.960 --> 01:18:04.910 align:middle line:84%
if the total number of balls is
around R to the alpha and N sub

01:18:04.910 --> 01:18:07.890 align:middle line:84%
r of x is less than
little r to the alpha.

01:18:07.890 --> 01:18:10.700 align:middle line:90%


01:18:10.700 --> 01:18:14.005 align:middle line:84%
This numerology is consistent
with how fractals behave.

01:18:14.005 --> 01:18:17.870 align:middle line:90%


01:18:17.870 --> 01:18:32.915 align:middle line:84%
And then you can make a
similar definition for a D. OK.

01:18:32.915 --> 01:18:41.330 align:middle line:90%


01:18:41.330 --> 01:18:43.130 align:middle line:84%
People might feel
it's not so clear

01:18:43.130 --> 01:18:45.840 align:middle line:84%
why to focus on this
particular set of conditions.

01:18:45.840 --> 01:18:48.020 align:middle line:90%
We can talk about it.

01:18:48.020 --> 01:18:53.960 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so the final
thing is that if you

01:18:53.960 --> 01:18:56.600 align:middle line:84%
take this set of
conditions, then we

01:18:56.600 --> 01:18:59.660 align:middle line:84%
can do a version in Euclidean
space of the conjecture

01:18:59.660 --> 01:19:03.410 align:middle line:84%
in theorem one and theorem two,
and all the numbers match up,

01:19:03.410 --> 01:19:05.750 align:middle line:84%
and we can prove a
version of theorem one

01:19:05.750 --> 01:19:08.512 align:middle line:84%
that looks just like that
with this double counting,

01:19:08.512 --> 01:19:10.220 align:middle line:84%
and we can prove a
version of theorem two

01:19:10.220 --> 01:19:13.550 align:middle line:84%
that looks just like that
with Fourier analysis.

01:19:13.550 --> 01:19:18.200 align:middle line:84%
And we have a conjecture
that looks just like that.

01:19:18.200 --> 01:19:23.210 align:middle line:84%
And the big recent result that
I hinted at in the first class

01:19:23.210 --> 01:19:28.790 align:middle line:84%
is the analog of that
conjecture is proven.

01:19:28.790 --> 01:19:31.620 align:middle line:84%
So at the beginning
of class on Tuesday,

01:19:31.620 --> 01:19:35.000 align:middle line:84%
I will write all
